to mock the Client object completely.  Previously the
tests were ensuring the right version of the client was
returned, but that required too much knowledge of glance's

commit_message:
Mock glance client object in version unit tests

This patch changes the glance client version unit tests
to mock the Client object completely.  Previously the
tests were ensuring the right version of the client was
returned, but that required too much knowledge of glance's
implementation and ended up breaking the tests when glance
changed the implementation details of the Client class.

The new code tests if cinder is calling the integration
point correctly for the version, rather than if glance
is correctly returning the right client; that should be
a glance test, not a cinder test.

Closes-Bug: 1366596
Change-Id: I979175e6c3b5f98076bde6d36ca52fb8b03009b8

commit_message:
Dividing get_action_class on two separate methods

 * We need separate method for constructing the Action class
   from raw parameters for passing them to executor since
   executor can not access to DB

Change-Id: I655d4a9bb767d61578768662c3678cc24a2ef22a

Rename action_factory to action_manager

 * action_factory is renamed to action_manager and
   is moved to services

'}, {'created': '2014-08-25 12:57:33.000000000', 'message': "Modify action_factory to store actions in DB

 * Action factory register actions in DB at starting
 * Added script tools/sync_db.sh for sync with db
   (Updates system actions, it is required before
   first Mistral launch)

 * Since we have to write all actions in DB, unit
   test are also modified:
    * Now in tearDown() we don't drop db at all,
      but just delete all workbooks.
    * Register actions operation is too much expensive
      operation so we create db and init actions in
      setupClass() method.
    * Added cleanUps to sqlAlchemy tests

Change-Id: If4416c4da5c05189126c109aa613a0303c1b7ef0

 * Action factory register actions in DB at starting
 * Added script tools/sync_db.sh for sync with db
   (Updates system actions, it is required before
   first Mistral launch)
 * Changed init Mistral in devstack: we must do
   sync_db before the launching.

 * Since we have to write all actions in DB, unit
   test are also modified:
    * Now in tearDown() we don't drop db at all,
      but just delete all workbooks.
    * Created heavy_init() method as a replacement
      setUpClass(), see comments in tests/base.py
    * Register actions operation is too much expensive
      operation so we create db and init actions in
      heavy_init() method.
    * Added cleanUps to sqlAlchemy tests

   runtime using action_factory

commit_message:
Modify action_factory to store actions in DB

 * Action factory register actions in DB at starting
 * Added script tools/sync_db.sh for sync with db
   (Updates system actions, it is required before
   first Mistral launch)
 * Changed init Mistral in devstack: we must do
   sync_db before the launching.

 * Since we have to write all actions in DB, unit
   test are also modified:
    * Now in tearDown() we don't drop db at all,
      but just delete all things except Actions.
    * Created heavy_init() method as a replacement
      setUpClass(), see comments in tests/base.py
    * Register actions operation is too much expensive
      operation so we create db and init actions in
      heavy_init() method.

TODO:
 * Provide executor info to construct action class in
   runtime using action_factory
 * Modify/write an instruction 'How to start Mistral'

Change-Id: If4416c4da5c05189126c109aa613a0303c1b7ef0

Add docs for enabling endpoint policy

Add documentation on how to enable endpoint policy, and link it
back to the configuration section of the Identity API.

commit_message:
Fix dn_startswith

The dn_startswith function was using the wrong expression to extract
the last part of the DN.

Change-Id: I98eefe499523c3f769c449bf7efa7cb8bb05926d
Partial-Bug: #1365787

On the commit I74261baac4fbf121826808ef55dfed960422b964, we found a
strange test result. Glance returns HTTP409 response if conflicting
image-id on "create an image" API, but Tempest raises a ServerFault
exception and it seems Tempest receives HTTP500/501.
This patch is only for digging this problem.

Change-Id: I8ab8a4204f352346ae1a4a79ecfa3b907218e4f8
'}]
commit_message:
Do not merge: [Glance] Add a test for conflicting image-id

On the commit I74261baac4fbf121826808ef55dfed960422b964, we found a
strange test result. Glance returns HTTP409 response if conflicting
image-id on "create an image" API, but Tempest raises a ServerFault
exception and it seems Tempest receives HTTP500/501.
This patch is only for digging this problem.

Change-Id: I8ab8a4204f352346ae1a4a79ecfa3b907218e4f8

Hi Iwamoto, do you have a stacktrace for this? Even though this change will let you log successfully, it won't get rid of the error completely."}, {'account_id': 9200, 'date': '2014-08-27 07:29:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Here it is.

http://paste.openstack.org/show/100867/

On whether this patch fixes exceptions, it's half true and half false. An exception will happen if another bind_router call is made from auto_schedule_routers.

The real problem is the DBDuplicateEntry handling isn't quite useful when called from auto_schedule_routers (from a loop and with an enclosing transaction)."}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2014-08-29 06:00:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi, sorry it took me a whole to get back here.

> On whether this patch fixes exceptions, it's half true and half false. An exception will happen if another bind_router call is made from auto_schedule_routers.

Correct, even though the exception won't be raised when accessing the agent id, the rollback is still being issued, which then will trigger an InvalidRequestError exception.

> The real problem is the DBDuplicateEntry handling isn't quite useful when called from auto_schedule_routers (from a loop and with an enclosing transaction).

IMO, the real problem is the lack of use of SAVEPOINTS. As a matter of fact, using savepoints (begin_nested() in sqlalchemy parlance) will address the very problem of rolling back a sub-transactions. Which is what capturing DBDuplicateError error is for.

Having said that, do you know if DBDuplicateError is raised intermittently in the context of auto_schedule_routers? Or is it a persistent fault? In the latter case, I think we'd need to nail down why this happens."}, {'account_id': 9200, 'date': '2014-08-29 06:17:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi,

in my case DBDuplicateError is due to a bug in the l3 HA patch, IIUC.  But debug logs should work correctly even if there's such a bug, since the purpose of debug logs are to help diagnose them.

BTW, I'm on vacation next week.  Sorry for inconvenience."}, {'account_id': 9200, 'date': '2014-09-08 01:16:40.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

a different fix was merged'}]

commit_message:
Fix bind_router debug log when called inside a transaction

If there is an outer transaction, the access to chosen_agent.id in the
except clause will fail.  To avoid this, save the value beforehand.

Change-Id: Ib3ebd2d12eb9579ff29cfde9d9bf8215dd9abd74
Closes-Bug: 1360104

commit_message:
Fixed stack.sh environment variables setting issue [bug #1316326]

When a user without proper privilege tries to execute stack.sh to
install Openstack, stack.sh will failed and create a lot of
null environment variables to affect the following scripts
because of no permission to access related files.
This fix will check the exit status to source environments,
if return code not 0, the stack.sh will quit and not produce null
envionment variables to affect next running.
Closes-Bug: 1316326

Change-Id: I4006cb122fa9d850fea8d22cf444f6704709dd2b

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-28 10:40:21.000000000', 'message': 'Fix condition of screen process check

This commit fixes the initial sanity check for screen process.
SCREEN_NAME is empty in the sanity check condition. Therefore,
when the screen socket path contains the digits, the condition
returns always true even if the screen is not running. This is
not an expected behavior.

Change-Id: I022ed1099169a3549b7e31883abe33d6298f6fa5
Closes-Bug: #1362091
'}, {'created': '2014-08-29 10:43:33.000000000', 'message': 'Move checks of "run as root" and "screen is already running" after stackrc

STACK_USER and SCREEN_NAME in these checks are defined in stackrc. This
commit moves these checks after reading stackrc.

Change-Id: I022ed1099169a3549b7e31883abe33d6298f6fa5
Closes-Bug: #1362091
'}, {'created': '2014-08-30 13:44:05.000000000', 'message': 'Fix to avoid undefined variables in initial sanity checks

This commit moves check to see if screen is already running after reading
stackrc, and changes messages in check if root is running DevStack.
STACK_USER is defined in stackrc, and SCREEN_NAME can be replaced with
"a non-root account".

Change-Id: I022ed1099169a3549b7e31883abe33d6298f6fa5
Closes-Bug: #1362091

commit_message:
Fix to avoid undefined variables in initial sanity checks

This commit moves check to see if screen is already running after reading
stackrc, and changes messages in check if root is running DevStack.
STACK_USER is defined in stackrc, and SCREEN_NAME can be replaced with
"a non-root account".

Change-Id: I022ed1099169a3549b7e31883abe33d6298f6fa5
Closes-Bug: #1362091

commit_message:
Use oslotest rather than copying helpers

The basic test setup is now handled by oslotest and the recommended way
of setting up tests should be to use that.

This theoretically means we should be able to remove testtools from
test-requirements.txt however it has been left as it will likely be
needed later.

Fixtures was removed as a dependency because commonly the required
fixtures would have been set up by oslotest.

Change-Id: I7fa71207ef56ce308fbe4e7a77fa3b9a7e2444ae

commit_message:
Fix indentation in tox.ini

Previously, a tab was used to indent a line with a block of code which
otherwise uses eight spaces, causing it to display strangely in text
editors which do not have tabstop=8 set.

TrivialFix

Change-Id: I99a432373beebac912df88e6685db26e738bf654

commit_message:
Revert "Cisco DFA ML2 Mechanism Driver"

This reverts commit 3680fd61c9a1cceaa011b4d0d37d235abf490c50.

The reverted patch incorrectly ties with Keystone and should have never been
approved since the approved version only partially addressed review concerns.

This revert also ensure migration timeline integrity.

commit_message:
Allow _poll_bandwidth_usage task to hit slave

Deployments that have a slave_connection configured can offload
read queries generated by this periodic task there. For
deployments with no slave, behavior remains the same.

Change-Id: Ibf27cdb94bc9b8c50066207c6285666cb29ebbf6
Blueprint: juno-slaveification

commit_message:
Ignore 'dynamic' addr flag on bridge configuration

When setting the bridge up, if that flag is present but not
ignored, the delete command will fail and may leave the
interface and the bridge in an inconsistent state.

Closes-Bug: #1274611
Related-Bug: #1077066
Change-Id: Id8bcd76f44b7e7502e0ed64ca85eb6b5983704fd
(cherry picked from commit 0d447f6edd406547e828c592823ac6624e56e91f)

commit_message:
Add nested/hierarchical state machine support

Nested/hierarchical state machines have a bunch of useful
properties that it would be great to have for the projects
that want to use it...

To name a few:

- The ability to reduce state and transition duplication
  by the ability of a hierarchical state machine to be
  able to *delegate* to a parent state machine on unknown
  events.
- Easier to understand and reduced state machines size; state
  machines at each level of the hierarchy can be simplified
  to only handle states they are made for (do one and only one
  thing well).
- Easier to compose machines; machines can be created that
  do one set of actions and states reliably, and this machine
  can be included in another machine that wants to use that
  same functionality.
- More...

Change-Id: I47812809aa9a6fd00ad7ee170be859d06e953c38

[{'created': '2014-08-26 02:43:46.000000000', 'message': 'Support for using pre created users (part 1)

This patch covers next topics:

1) Changes db deploymnet model to store admin endpoint and list of
   non-admin users

2) Changes objects.deployment to have this admin and users instead of
   endpoints

3) Changes input format of ExistingCloud engine, to make it easy to
   pass users & admins

4) Changes engine.bind method to accept admin and list of users

5) Code cleanup related to removing list of endpoints and making
   admin/non-admin stuff

6) Fixing all related tests

In next patch we should drop default "users" context and use users
from deployment if they are passed.

commit_message:
Support for benchmarking with existing users (part 1)

This patch covers next topics:

1) Changes db deploymnet model to store admin endpoint and list of
   non-admin users

2) Changes objects.deployment to have this admin and users instead of
   endpoints

3) Changes input format of ExistingCloud engine, to make it easy to
   pass users & admins

4) Changes engine.bind method to accept admin and list of users

5) Code cleanup related to removing list of endpoints and making
   admin/non-admin stuff

6) Fix CLI code related to deployment model change

7) Fix docs & samples

8) Fixing all related tests

In next patch we should drop default "users" context and use users
from deployment if they are passed.

Change-Id: Ifb469d80c61ee5f26f313db75c98a6d496bcdb92

commit_message:
Fix wrong command for _rescan_multipath

The _run_multipath command is wrong in [1], it should be 'multipath -r'
not 'multipath - r'. And adds test for this.

[1]: https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/virt/libvirt/volume.py#L590

Change-Id: I3c5d12cc11988d65a8fc9e6143d26c2d1220d253
Closes-bug: 1362916

commit_message:
VMware: Fix return type of get_vnc_console()

Change I8f6a857b88659ee30b4aa1a25ac52d7e01156a68 changed the return type of
get_vnc_console(), but didn't update it in VMwareVCVMOps.

Closes-Bug: #1364849
Change-Id: I25edf0a19fa79439ed375ad128d0050718d04cb3

Add a binding capability to the Big Switch ML2 mechanism
driver to mark external ports as bound. This prevents them
from showing up with 'binding failed' even though the actual
fabric configuration happens on the port update operation.

Implements: blueprint bsn-ml2-ext-attach
Change-Id: I7b749ba5ef9a47b45be24f77656a10ed38e5e6ae
"}, {'created': '2014-09-01 01:26:20.000000000', 'message': "BSN: Bind external ports in ML2 driver

Add a binding capability to the Big Switch ML2 mechanism
driver to mark external ports as bound. Ports with the
owner type 'neutron:external' will be assigned to the first
VLAN segment available in the network. The port update operation
will then carry the HOST ID with the identifier to the backend
for the necessary fabric configuration.

Implements: blueprint bsn-ml2-ext-attach
Change-Id: I7b749ba5ef9a47b45be24f77656a10ed38e5e6ae

commit_message:
BSN: Bind external ports in ML2 driver

Add a binding capability to the Big Switch ML2 mechanism
driver to mark external ports as bound. Ports with the
owner type 'neutron:external_port' will be assigned to the first
VLAN segment available in the network. The port update operation
will then carry the HOST ID with the identifier to the backend
for the necessary fabric configuration.

Implements: blueprint bsn-ml2-ext-attach
Change-Id: I7b749ba5ef9a47b45be24f77656a10ed38e5e6ae

commit_message:
Add mox dependency

Some of our tests use mox, but oslotest no longer uses it, so when we
update oslotest we won't have it installed automatically any more.

Change-Id: Iee663a090259bdba0524d8400fd844d6ce950e1d

'}, {'created': '2014-07-14 23:18:08.000000000', 'message': 'Translate engine runner into a well defined state-machine

Instead of having a ad-hoc state-machine being used to perform
the various runtime actions (performed when a engine is ran) we
can gain a much more explict execution model by translating that
ad-hoc state machine to an explicit one instead.

This commit does just that, it adds a new fsm type that can be
used to create, define and run state-machines that respond to
various events (internal or external) and uses it in the runner action
engine module to run the previously implicit state-machine.

commit_message:
Translate the engine runner into a well defined state-machine

Instead of having a ad-hoc state-machine being used to perform
the various runtime actions (performed when a engine is ran) we
can gain a much more explict execution model by translating that
ad-hoc state machine to an explicit one instead...

This commit does just that, it adds a new fsm type that can be
used to create, define and run state-machines that respond to
various events (internal or external) and uses it in the runner action
engine module to run the previously ad-hc/implicit state-machine.

Implements blueprint runner-state-machine

Change-Id: Id35633a9de707f3ffb1a4b7e9619af1be009317f

commit_message:
Automatically initialize git when finished.

PBR will refuse to work or allow users to run tests until there is a git
repository set up. It is easier to just do this automatically than have
to explain it in the docs.

Change-Id: Ied9ccab2665c4542e2ec2ee42174c3e15e166880

commit_message:
VMware: Remove VMwareVCVMOps

This support is no longer needed as we only support the VC driver
since commit 1deb31f85a8f5d1e261b2cf1eddc537a5da7f60b.

The patch makes use of VMwareVMOps. All of the specific VC methods
are moved into this class.

partial blueprint vmware-spawn-refactor

Change-Id: Ieb2198a956853c75855e3b4441cc3a893b2e6079

commit_message:
VMware: image user functions for spawn()

Refactor each mode of using cached images when configuring a newly
created virtual machine into their own functions.

DocImpact:
vmware_linked_clone image property is ignored when spawning an
image that is an ISO.

partial-blueprint: vmware-spawn-refactor

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

are run against master.

commit_message:
Add API schema for v2.1 access_ips extension

By defining the API schema, it is possible to separate the validation
code from the API method. The API method can be more simple.
In addition, a response of API validation error can be consistent for
the whole Nova API.

Partially implements blueprint v3-api-schema

Change-Id: I495e7538e5d8d67f19792dfa0427ab7a1b0068cf

recheck bug 1337245'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2014-07-10 13:39:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

This needs to be implemented as 'user set --password x' rather than a new command.  The CLI already has that defined for both v2 and v3.

OSC really doesn't discriminate between admin and not-admin commands since it doesn't have the policy to make that determination.

I do like the prompt addition to get_password()."}, {'account_id': 7073, 'date': '2014-07-10 13:53:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Actually that was my first idea before i found some problems with it.

1. openstack user set expect a <user-id>, users that want to change there own password doesn't specially know about there user id. 

2. keystoneclient.users.change_password (https://github.com/openstack/python-keystoneclient/blob/0.9.0/keystoneclient/v3/users.py#L139) doesn't accept a user-id b/c it only allow to change "current user" password.

3. Admin user can use "openstack user set --password" to update user password and they should not be required to enter the current password i.e. not using keystoneclient.users.change_password but instead it should user  keystoneclient.users.update.

4. Passing multiple argument beside "password" to "openstack user set" doesn't make any sense b/c they will fail if the user is not admin.

For example if a normal user do and considering that user use default policy.json:

$ openstack user set --password .... --email ... <user-id>
   
We will be sending 2 request one using keystoneclient.users.change_password the other is keystoneclient.users.update, while the first one will succeed the last one will fail b/c "identity:user_update" require "rule:cloud_admin or rule:admin_and_matching_target_user_domain_id".

Thoughts ?'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-10 13:57:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

1. You can use nargs to make the positional argument <user>, optionally

2. Doesn't look like you ever have to submit the user_id, keystoneclient fetches it from the client session created.

3. We can do "openstack user set --new-password --old-password" and based on the parsed_args values, specifically call client.update_password, instead of client.update.

4. If the user supplies other args with --new-password and --old-password then break with an error message.'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2014-07-10 15:18:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I don't want a new command, but users not even being able to look up their own ID really sucks.  However, that's a reasonable test for admin-ness and can be used to properly dispatch the command handling without adding yet another round trip.

Re other options in the command, if not admin, issue a warning and attempt the user-mode password change anyway?

When in the user-change-pw section, if --password and/or --old-password are not given, do the prompting as required.  However, I'm thinking we should have the option to prompt for --password as admin too in order to allow not putting the new password on a plaintext command-line, similar to the tricks using passwd(1).

pseudocode:

if (lookup user)
    # admin stuffs as now
    if --password == '-'   # or '' if nargs is used
        prompt for password
    users.update()
else
    # user
    if --old-password not present or --old-password == '-'    # or '' if nargs is used
        prompt for old password
    if --password not present or --password == '-'   # or '' if nargs is used
        prompt for password
    users.change_password()

FWIW, I'm not a fan of --password-prompt, although sudo does have '-S' to do the same thing.  This may be the one time nargs is useful even with the ambiguity, --password == None forces a prompt.  Nargs on both --password and user may be tricky... ;)"}, {'account_id': 7073, 'date': '2014-07-10 16:31:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Thanks both for the thoughtful review,

@Steve

Remarks about the numbered point above:

  2. I was actually referring to the fact that a <user-id> + a call to ks.users.update_password doesn't make sense, but we can maybe solve this with making <user-id> optional.

   4. Prompting for password is more secure way of changing a password, relaying and requiring  --new-password --old-password to be set is IMHO quiet bad, right ?

@Dean:

I don't think it's a reasonable test, it all depend on the policies user may be allowed to know his own id or know, a deployer may choose to set  "identity:get_user": "rule:cloud_admin or rule:admin_or_owner"  for example, what we can do is add to that test wether user-id supplied in argument is equal to ``identity_client.users.api.user_id``, but just to stretch how this will look use case wise so that we are in the same page:

    # Update own password by prompting. 
    $ openstack user set  --password-prompt

    # Either <user-id> is current user id or it's another <user-id>, in case
    # user-id is the current user id this will call update_password, this of
    # course will require even admin to give his current password.
    $ openstack user set --password-prompt <user-id> 

    # As admin, user can't update both field at once b/c if we allow this for
    # admin, no admin user will get a nasty error not knowing wether his
    # password did change or no check point 4 above.
    $ openstack user set  --password "foo" --email "foo@example.com"

Another solution will be EAFP (try: update_user(...)  except AuthorizationError: change_password()), but I really dislike this solution, to be fair I like another command b/c it state with no magic (if this and that) that user want to change his own password plain and simple KISS :)

To state the obvious b/c we are talking about identity:user_update policy rule whenever I say admin I am actually referring to who ever is allowed to do the update action e.g.  "identity:user_update": "role:superman".

Thoughts ?'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2014-07-10 22:59:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I agree it needs to be simple and my insistence on sticking with 'user set' is really hindering that, eh?

A user changing their own password is a pretty unique action (Steve, is there anything similar with any of the other backends? oauth for example?).

How about we model 'user password' after passwd(1)?  That's the entire command, at least for non-admin.  Maybe we want to let admin use that to change others, like root and passwd, but maybe not?

Since this is just for end-users, I'd argue that we should not have a command-line option for providing either the new or old passwords.  A user who wants to script that might be smart enough to know how to use expect?  Or even just redirection?"}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2014-07-10 23:02:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I just noticed that get_password() bails if stdin is not a tty; I think we'd want it to read two (or three) lines from stdin without prompts in that case rather than throw an exception?"}, {'account_id': 6482, 'date': '2014-07-10 23:06:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Dean, I'm at the keystone hackathon, I asked around... nothing else in keystone does that, it's pretty special."}, {'account_id': 7073, 'date': '2014-07-11 09:13:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

> I agree it needs to be simple and my insistence on sticking with 'user set' is really hindering that, eh?

I think the discussion that we are having over how to do it with "user set" and the use cases that break while doing that prove the contrary :), and to not get me wrong I am surely not complain, I live for this kind of discussion :)

BTW is there something that require backward compatibility ? Remove an option from a existing command is kind of bad right ?  like --password from "user set" if that what you suggested ?

As to reading from stdin, please correct me if I am wrong but reading from it without blocking may not be as easy as it sound, in Unix we can use either an signal.alarm or select.select, and none of them is bullet proof, but windows will require something totally different ! Actually I don't mind removing the argument --password but I don't really see it as a problem if we go with a separate action for changing password.

I do like the idea of modeling over passwd(1) but without accepting positional argument "user", I think reflecting what the API offer (POST /users/{user_id}/password VS PATCH /users/{user_id}) and what the policy rules contain (identity:update_user VS identity:change_password) is a good idea, actually b/c OSC wasn't doing that where my confusion started that lead to a bug reported and to this patch, specially comparing to keystoneclient which I found more intuitive in this regard:

    $ keystone help
    ...
    user-password-update
                        Update user password.
    ...
    user-update         Update user's name, email, and enabled status.
    ...

Did I convince you already :) ? Thoughts ?'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-15 17:15:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

Starting check jobs.
http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 4, 'date': '2014-07-15 17:15:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(apologies for not reading through *all* the discussion here, but...) I do think that openstackclient needs to distinguish between an administrative password reset operation (which does not require the current password), and a user's self-service password update/rotation operation (which requires the current password)... so I like the direction of the current change, but I wouldn't want an admin to assume he/she needs the user's password to do a "user password set."'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-15 18:29:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

commit_message:
Add action 'user password set' for identiy v3

This new action will allow a user to change their own password by
either providing the new password as an argument (--password) or by
being prompted to enter the new password.
In both cases user will be prompted to enter their current password
as required by the v3 API.

Closes-Bug: #1337245
Change-Id: I5e1e0fd2b46a4502318da57f7cce2b236fb2d93d

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-04 14:18:38.000000000', 'message': "Check for namedtuple_as_object support before using it

Commit ad248f6658d572f3f4721f804325db754e9c931d introduced the usage of
the namedtuple_as_object kwarg if using simplejson.

However, that kwarg isn't available until simplejson 2.2.0 which is a
problem for anyone running a RHEL/CentOS 6 distribution.

Normally this would not be a big deal since we can bump minimum required
versions but in this case simplejson is an optional runtime dependency
so most projects don't list it in their requirements.txt files.  So if
you are running with simplejson < 2.2.0 (you might not even know it) and
upgrade, things are going to get sad very quick.

Rather than assume people will be at the right level or figure it out,
let's be smarter and just check if the kwarg is available in the version
of simplejson we're using.  If we don't have a new enough version of
simplejson then fallback to using json despite the performance issues
on python 2.6.

This can be removed in Kilo when python 2.6 support is dropped so this
should be short-term workaround that saves some headaches once Juno is
released.

Closes-Bug: #1361230

Change-Id: Iadc2d28a1a0b125a34ed08344673c6b4a8a758e9
(cherry picked from commit 4d61c826eff57e112417e948f7166e8b29425f4a)

commit_message:
Check for namedtuple_as_object support before using it

Commit ad248f6658d572f3f4721f804325db754e9c931d introduced the usage of
the namedtuple_as_object kwarg if using simplejson.

However, that kwarg isn't available until simplejson 2.2.0 which is a
problem for anyone running a RHEL/CentOS 6 distribution.

Normally this would not be a big deal since we can bump minimum required
versions but in this case simplejson is an optional runtime dependency
so most projects don't list it in their requirements.txt files.  So if
you are running with simplejson < 2.2.0 (you might not even know it) and
upgrade, things are going to get sad very quick.

Rather than assume people will be at the right level or figure it out,
let's be smarter and just check if the kwarg is available in the version
of simplejson we're using.  If we don't have a new enough version of
simplejson then fallback to using json despite the performance issues
on python 2.6.

This can be removed in Kilo when python 2.6 support is dropped so this
should be short-term workaround that saves some headaches once Juno is
released.

Closes-Bug: #1361230

Change-Id: Iadc2d28a1a0b125a34ed08344673c6b4a8a758e9
(cherry picked from commit 4d61c826eff57e112417e948f7166e8b29425f4a)

commit_message:
Convert v3 ExtendedAvailabilityZone api to v2.1

This patch changes v3 ExtendedAvailabilityZone API to v2.1
and makes v2 unit tests share between v2 and v2.1.

The differences between v2 and v3 are described on the wiki page
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/NovaAPIv2tov3.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I49baff38b7a9dabd40550267c2119fe84137594f

commit_message:
Add oslo.concurrency and oslo.middleware

Install the oslo.concurrency and oslo.middleware libraries from source so
the gate tests are run against master.

Change-Id: I194fc160127ab8b4b7d0086586d8ba7f92c67076

commit_message:
Don't run lbaas scenario test as smoke test

Load Balancer as a service  is not part of neutron's primary
functionality, it is one of the advanced services that is not fully
baked yet. As part of the effort to only test advanced services against
neutron and not against all projects, drop this test from smoke.

Related patch: Ib315d30ff3c4463203f7ebe00e159a9680cf1616

Change-Id: I43239e9dc3e99e382ea12fb94f940f9029f4e488

commit_message:
Unordered dicts and lists causes variable results

The unordered dict and lists causes variable results.  The user
may see different results and tests can fail.  Might as well make
this more consistent.

Change-Id: I7045b40b44cbf3ee0f2ca79c6ea0d279b6d8cfe3

virt/driver get_serial_console

commit_message:
Fix handling of arguments in autohelp-wrapper

The shift should happen after the final processing, otherwise
getopts aborts if more than one parameter is given.

commit_message:
Handle ExternalNetworkAttachForbidden exception

When creating an instance and assigning a public network
to it without admin authority, ExternalNetworkAttachForbidden
will be raised. But this exception is not handled in V3 api.

Change-Id: Id70d8eaa704fd82cef1afdb65756d75cb56fbdce
Closes-Bug: #1353949

commit_message:
Implements sync mechanism between Neutron and Nuage VSD

This will sync resources between Neutron and VSD based on
the configuration parameters. "enable_sync" will enable/disable
the sync and "sync_interval" will control the time interval
between consecutive sync cycles.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I6730bf0166dfd1e35795b679293a2831b5afbc75
Implements: blueprint nuage-neutron-sync

commit_message:
Port used_limits & used_limits_for_admin into v2.1

The used_limits & used_limits_for_admin is removed from v3 API.
For now, we need porting it back. And also try to share unittests
between v2 and v2.1.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I57199273dcaf20b0b6618dfb436a92f04b139f52

commit_message:
Big Switch: Bind IVS ports in ML2 driver

Add support to bind IVS ports in the Big Switch ML2
mechanism driver. The backend controller will be checked
to determine if a host is connected using the Indigo vswitch.
If so, the mechanism driver will mark it as bound since
it will be provisioned by the backend controller.

Implements: blueprint bsn-ml2-bind-ivs
Change-Id: Ic481fc31c8c123899fddf8185c32f127dff53b7a

commit_message:
Fix use of nonexistent class variable in accounts

This commit fixes cases in tempest.common.accounts cases where some
methods were attempting to use non-existent class level variables.
It also improves the get_hash methods and calls to remove_hash.

Co-Authored-By: Andrea Frittoli <andrea.frittoli@hp.com>
Change-Id: I30cf59b981e0db3a3e50357a8db489519767c0ca

commit_message:
Add API schema for v2.1 "update a server" API

Some v2.1 APIs(create/update/rebuild server) contains the API
extension feature, it searches extension methods with its method
name and operates them automatically.
It is necessary to change the API schemas also automatically based
on the API extension loading condition, because the API extensions
add API parameters.

This patch adds API schema extensions which are implemented with the
same mechanism (stevedore library) as the API extension for "update
a server" extensions.

Partially implements blueprint v3-api-schema

Change-Id: I2f80a994bc69153bd40251827aad0479876a94ab

commit_message:
Add API schema for v2.1 "rebuild a server" API

Some v2.1 APIs(create/update/rebuild server) contains the API
extension feature, it searches extension methods with its method
name and operates them automatically.
It is necessary to change the API schemas also automatically based
on the API extension loading condition, because the API extensions
add API parameters.

This patch adds API schema extensions which are implemented with the
same mechanism (stevedore library) as the API extension for "rebuild
a server" extensions.

Partially implements blueprint v3-api-schema

Change-Id: Ibfdd99966335d062cde4cc1d9ab3b63bc82ed0b6

commit_message:
Setup localization properly

To start translation of swift, we need to initially import the
translation file - and place it at the proper place so that
the usual CI scripts can handle it.

The proper place is for all python projects
$PROJECT/locale/$PROJECT.pot, so move locale/$PROJECT.pot to the new
location and regenerate the file.

Update setup.cfg with the new paths.

Further imports will be done by the OpenStack Proposal bot.

Change-Id: Ide4da91f2af71db529f4a06d6b1e30ba79883506
Partial-Bug: #608725
Closes-Bug: #1082805

commit_message:
Fixed incorrect position of modal container.

After updating to bootrap 3, the position of the modal
container is incorrect when you scroll down on a page
then select an action button towards the top of the page that brings up
a modal dialog.  The dialog is displayed off the bottom of the screen.

I couldnt find a graceful way to fix the css issue, so I had to over-
ride a bootstrap css rule using !important.

Change-Id: I5539692a6657555e08e893339098159306836021
Closes-bug: #1353897

commit_message:
Enabled qemu memory balloon stats

We can get vm memory stats from libvirt API
'virDomainMemoryStats', it help telemetry module
like as: Ceilometer to collect vm memory usage,
but by default the memory statistical feature is
disable in qemu, we need to add stats period
in order to enabled memory statistical.

DocImpact: Adds mem_stats_period_seconds to
the [libvirt] group of nova.conf

Change-Id: Ie5c615565ffbe5d70394f2ddba162ace14abe24e

commit_message:
Make unit tests not depend on random hash seed

This commit fixes the places in the tempest unit tests which were
dependent on the python hashseed being 0. They were mostly issues of
expectations, either explicit or inadvertently implicit, on dict or
list ordering.

Change-Id: Iab72ed4d52765de744804e6202ee4bf0664988c5

commit_message:
Remove pre-icehouse rpc client API compat

The compute rpc API was at version 3.23 for the Icehouse release.
Since we only support live upgrades from N-1 to N (Icehouse to Juno),
we can remove old rpc client support for versions that were
pre-Icehouse release.  This patch does that for the compute rpcapi.

Change-Id: Ice20b141dbe28de02e125fa5ced1dbc286ba2ee3

commit_message:
Use netifaces to lookup IP address on guest agent

The current way of looking up the IP address on the guest
doesn't correctly work across all platforms. Use netifaces
instead which works correctly across all platforms.

Change-Id: I3d5febb1dd801fdf7801613cd843e7c00f308016

commit_message:
Cleanup rename of get_compute_ports_on_host_by_subnet

A recent merge [1] renamed this method to remove "compute_" from the
name.  Unfortunately, the rename was not done thoroughly.  This patch
cleans that up.  No bug is referenced since this is an obvious
ommission in a recent patch.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/114141/

Change-Id: I8320bc8deb6dcda586ccff01120270b3ce257ea2

commit_message:
Cisco N1kv plugin to send subtype on network profile creation

Make sure that the cisco n1kv neutron plugin sends the sub_type too
when a overlay network profile is created

Change-Id: I37e63131039077fa80a28fe725c09f0307acc2ea
Closes-Bug: 1357125
(cherry picked from commit e6ffc08de72a21980cde38d1a716d429311f7819)

commit_message:
Port image-size extension to work in v2.1/v3 framework

Ports v2 image-size extension and adapts it to the v2.1/v3 API
framework. API behaviour is identical with the exception
that there is no support for XML. Also

- unittest code modified to share testing with both v2/v2.1
- Adds expected error decorators for API methods

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I44f3d35b3d888e2f4429ca0788d74b9b0cce9494

subject: Port v2 image_metadata extension to work in v2.1(v3) framework

commit_message:
Port v2 image_metadata extension to work in v2.1(v3) framework

Port v2 image_metadata extension and adapts it to the v2.1/v3 API
framework. API behaviour is identical with the exception that
there is no support for XML. Also

- unittest code modified to share existing testing with both
  v2/v2.1
- Adds expected error decorators for API methods
- Adds API samples

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: Ibc8dc897f3449a1c70bc7ac1510445f48fddb291

Align swift's store API

swift's store get method was lacking of 2 keyword arguments. This patch
adds them to the API.

Change-Id: I8f67380b4ca07261bc3d4e6fbd201189d1087a96

commit_message:
Add `OPTIONS` attribute to swift.Store function

Swift uses a function to wrap the final store instance and choose
between a SingleTenant/MultiTenant store. This patch adds the `OPTIONS`
attribute, found in all other store classes, in order to be able to
register the store options without actually creating an instance of the
Store - just like in every other store.

Iterate over swift/utils.py options, in order to add a deprecate options
for each one of those.

Change-Id: I581cdf5e8e5c112e129c2f0d62ad2a9caf19383b

commit_message:
Add missing stores to setup.cfg

Add the missing stores to setup.cfg and add the old stores to keep
backwards compatibility. In addition, raise an error if a store
entry_point is not found.

Set group for DeprecatedOpts

Deprecated options' group must be explicitly set, otherwise it'll lookup
the old option in the group the new one was registered in.

Change-Id: Idd0abd639373d9769ba6c520604f0e46a9b6f1ec

commit_message:
Complete random_access for the filesystem store

This patch completes the support for random_access for the filesystem
store. It adds the required tests and modifies `ChunkFile` in a way that
it keeps backwards compatibility and adds support for this feature.

Change-Id: Ifaf6488165616c87debbb86b9dffa780df8c4b5f
Implements-blueprint: restartable-image-download

commit_message:
Register store's configs w/o creating instances

Instead of invoking the each store to register the config options, we
should just load the class and access `OPTIONS` from there. The old
attempt for config options registration is kept for other purposes.

Change-Id: I5545c1bd0ff0fd613cd40aadd87aaa4cbf2685ac

commit_message:
Add deprecated options support for storage drivers

Instead of requiring all storage driver options to be migrated
immediately, provide an upgrade path by supporting all config options
that used to be under the `DEFAULT` section.

Change-Id: Id978830c67f6c93b18e73cc16da92b99702357f5

commit_message:
Refactor searchutils module to base entity classes

Instead of a special module with search methods for different entities (by query),
implement them inside corresponding classes. Modify the "rally info" code appropriately.

Change-Id: Iba6c25752a191eedfc483bac2b4475bba5aa1e58

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-06-13 17:46:40.000000000', 'message': 'libvirt: persist lxc attached volumes across reboots and power down

Currently, attach volumes to a LXC instance will be lost, when
hard rebooting or powering it down.
Adjusting the get_storage_config() to attach volumes for lxc as well.
The change will add all volumes to the instance config, a part from
the rood device mapping.
Using the filter_root_bdm() generator from block_device module, to
filter out the root device mapping, when (re)creating a LXC instance.

Co-authored-by: Sam Morrison<sorrison@gmail.com>
Closes-Bug: #1269990
Change-Id: I0aa227ede5fca065c6da15506d8cc4391d993e20

hard rebooting or powering it down.

the root device mapping.

from block_device module, will be used to exclude the root device
mapping for a domain configuration.

commit_message:
libvirt: persist lxc attached volumes across reboots and power down

Currently, attached volumes to a LXC instance will be lost, when
hard rebooting or powering it down.
Adjusting the get_storage_config() to include LXC volumes in the
domain configuration.
The change will add all volumes to the instance config, a part from
the root device mapping.
When (re)creating a LXC instance, get_bdms_to_connect() generator
from block_device module, will be used to exclude the root device
mapping for a domain configuration.

Co-authored-by: Sam Morrison<sorrison@gmail.com>
Closes-Bug: #1269990
Change-Id: I0aa227ede5fca065c6da15506d8cc4391d993e20

commit_message:
Deprecate the V1 API

This gives a warning for using the V1 API in Juno and encourages users
to switch to V2 before the K release where it will be removed.

DocImpact
Implements blueprint deprecate-v1-api
Change-Id: I89eb9eb2a7819edb2a97b2ea2b5239a89124ca4d

commit_message:
Revert "Skip functional l3 agent test"

This reverts commit 0918ce91e5af5100ee3a4fcd6861741c4f00ac41. The
specified commit skipped a test which caused non-deterministic gate
failures, but the actual reason for the failures was found and fixed
so the skip is no longer needed.

Related-bug: #1358206
Related-bug: #1364171
Change-Id: I9b0d9ad9ad8b62ee92877fc0a6db0323604433ac

commit_message:
Pull dstat logic into its own function so grenade can use it

In order to use dstat on the new side of grenade, pull dstat code into
its own lib with the function start_dstat

Change-Id: I5c908d594a6f3a90ed4b3f744002bf606841cf07

commit_message:
Move parts of action engine tests to a subdirectory

To match how we have a worker_based subdirectory for
its specific tests lets start moving pieces of the action
engine specific tests to its own directory as well and
move more in the future as well.

Change-Id: I003b07a95259ba18b961834515121243e27d7456

1. Have the runner yield the final set of failures instead of
   raising them, this allows the same yield syntax to be used

   stop the action engines task executor.

   in (1) that the runner yields back failures instead of raising them
   itself.

commit_message:
Tweak engine iteration 'close-up shop' runtime path

1. Have the runner yield the final set of failures instead of
   raising them, this allows the same yield syntax to be used
   for all exit points that the runner run_iter() produces and
   now raise failures from the main engine run loop to match this
   change.
2. Use a context manager instead of try/finally to start and
   stop the action engines task executor (teenie niceness...)
3. When the engine run_iter() is used and the generator that is
   returned is closed, instead of breaking from the run loop, which
   can leave running tasks incomplete instead continue running and
   signal to the runner that the engine has suspended itself. This
   ensures that the running atoms are not lost when the generator from
   run_iter() is closed (for whatever reason) before finishing.

Also adds a bunch of useful tests that directly test the runner instead
of the indirect testing that we were doing before.

Fixes bug 1361013

Change-Id: I1b598e26f0b3877c8f7004f87bacdb7f5e9c9897

commit_message:
Add attributes to cell in a table depending on data

This feature helps users to selectively add attributes to cells
within a table based on the value in the cell. An example of why
this might be useful is cases where we want to display a short
description of what data in a given cell means.

This has been implemented by adding a new property to the Column
class called the 'cell_attributes_getter'. This attribute is a
callable which returns a dictionary with the html attributes and
their values. The attribute defined in this dictionary can include
any HTML global attributes

Change-Id: I9e9aa1bc32e7afd1a62a69dc13ef0ed0d0e748c4

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-20 00:47:48.000000000', 'message': "Implement OS::Heat::StructuredDeployments

This is a resource which subclasses ResourceGroup to deploy a group
of OS::Heat::StructuredDeployment resources

The main difference in properties between this resource and
OS::Heat::StructuredDeployment is that it has a 'servers' property
instead of 'server'. The servers property expects a map of
resource-name/nova-uuid pairs. The resource name is used as the
deployment resource name inside the group, and the nova-uuid is used
as the server to deploy to.

This resource also inherits the index_var property from ResourceGroup.

Change-Id: I5f9603c68bb7cd81ef60a6b2ba965e5b8e93887a
Implements-Blueprint: deployment-multiple-servers
"}, {'created': '2014-08-27 00:14:04.000000000', 'message': "Implement OS::Heat::StructuredDeployments

commit_message:
Implement OS::Heat::SoftwareDeployments

This is a resource which subclasses ResourceGroup to deploy a group
of OS::Heat::SoftwareDeployment resources

The main difference in properties between this resource and
OS::Heat::SoftwareDeployment is that it has a 'servers' property
instead of 'server'. The servers property expects a map of
resource-name/nova-uuid pairs. The resource name is used as the
deployment resource name inside the group, and the nova-uuid is used
as the server to deploy to.

The attributes deploy_stdouts, deploy_stderrs, deploy_status_codes
each return a map where the key is the server name and the value
is the respective attribute from the deployment resource.

Change-Id: Ide1e8fb57d45062e5d459b484135a5cad6d2c7dc
Partial-Blueprint: deployment-multiple-servers

commit_message:
Provide access to outputs from OS::Heat::ResourceGroup

To align with the related OS::Heat::AutoScalingGroup change:
Ib9e830e0c54602ac456d64179e1df30f0778906d

This adds an 'attributes' attribute to the OS::Heat::ResourceGroup resource
so that the following:
  {'get_attr': ['my_asg', 'attributes', 'networks', '<network_name>', 0]}
returns a mapping from resource names to the corresponding IP addresses.

There is no need for an outputs_list attribute since the following already
returns a list:
  {'get_attr': ['my_rg', 'networks', '<network_name>', 0]}

To align ResourceGroup with OS::Heat::AutoScalingGroup, there will
be a proposed change to OS::Heat::AutoScalingGroup to rename the
following attributes:
- outputs -> attributes
- outputs_list -> attributes_list

Change-Id: Id51f23533ae75ca5d883a4f67e75ac9513a67264

commit_message:
ResourceGroup make do_prop_replace class method

This refactor allows subclasses to override _do_prop_replace so
that properties can be populated by the specific needs of the subclass.

Change-Id: I1ebe382b8efd010e128fa9c452d5ddb580237c1e
Partial-Blueprint: deployment-multiple-servers

commit_message:
Fix interface IP address for DVR with gateway

when an interface is added to a router with gateway, the method
internal_network_added(..) incorrectly configures the IP address
of the new snat interface same as the IP address of the new
subnet interface.

Change-Id: I00d4ff1105a443b89b28359249b8e83fb4c1d157
Closes-bug: #1355087

commit_message:
Reset task state 'migrating' on nova compute restart

This change has the compute manager's init_instance method check
for a task state set to 'migrating' and resets the task state to
None, so that live migrations that were pending when the compute
service went down do not result in instances that are perpetually
stuck in 'migrating' task state.

Change-Id: If23ea983cc048f317daae594f420a643f1bfe6ac
Closes-Bug: #1339823

commit_message:
Check for change before container replicator updates db

As described in the related bug report, unnecessary updates
to the container db during replication can impact object
object GET performance in certain circumstances.

This patch changes swift/container/replicator.py so that
calls to merge_timestamps and update_reconciler_sync
are conditional on values having actually changed.

Related-Bug: 1332025
Change-Id: If498251656500ed7a3d7ca4b109ea1079b8513c2

[{'created': '2014-08-20 10:15:30.000000000', 'message': "Generate IdP Metadata with keystone-manage.

For the proper federation setup a Identity Provider peer needs to
generate a metadata later to be consumed by a federated Service
Providers. Since metadata content doesn't change very often it's advised
to generate a static file and later read its content on demand (this is
out of the scope of this patch). This patch adds required functionality
for utilizing federation.idp.MetadataGenerator class from a
keystone-manage command line tool. Generated metadata will be redirected
to the stdout.

Change-Id: Ifed1f4e4ede0276b3aba22aa9e236e5e74e2ed93
Implements: bp keystone-to-keystone-federation

commit_message:
Generate IdP Metadata with keystone-manage.

For proper federation setup, an Identity Provider peer needs to
generate metadata that can later be consumed by a federated Service
Provider. Since metadata content doesn't change very often it's
advised to generate a static file and later read its content on demand
(this is out of the scope of this patch). This patch adds required
functionality for utilizing the federation.idp.MetadataGenerator class
from a keystone-manage command line tool. Generated metadata will
be redirected to the stdout.

Change-Id: Ifed1f4e4ede0276b3aba22aa9e236e5e74e2ed93
Implements: bp keystone-to-keystone-federation

commit_message:
Error limit the right node on object PUT

If any node had an error on object PUT, the proxy would count the
error against the last-connected-to node instead of the one with the
error. Now it counts the error against the right node.

Change-Id: I884eb73cebe0c723473a6d5e390a148fcad0d3ed

commit_message:
Change app.restapi to app.client_manager.session

This is step 1 toward using Keystone client's session.Session as the
primary session/requests interface in OSC.

* Move the session create into ClientManager and rename 'restapi' attribute to 'session'
* Set up ClientManager and session loggers
* Fix container and object command references to restapi/api

Change-Id: I013d81520b336c7a6422cd22c05d1d65655e64f8

commit_message:
Collect javelin2 log

As of Id5c0dfeaf8e7e9ed1d54f51c54e6e5c65b1361fa javelin will now log to
the file javelin.log collect this log for debugging.

Check for the files existence before attempting to collect to allow this
patch to land before the grenade patch lands.

Change-Id: I787c08506d9a4d12081b5b5b16d752d5147f8e72

commit_message:
Move cli tests into service subdirectories

This commit takes the cli tests and moves them into service specific directories. This is 
done in lieu of using a service decorator to properly tag the test as using a particular
service. This should be less error prone then adding a decorator to each test case. It also
is useful for projects that have more than one cli interface being tested by making the grouping by service more explicit.

Partially implements bp add-service-tags

[{'created': '2014-08-29 18:17:47.000000000', 'message': "Check for namedtuple_as_object support before using it

Commit ad248f6658d572f3f4721f804325db754e9c931d introduced the usage of
the namedtuple_as_object kwarg if using simplejson.

However, that kwarg isn't available until simplejson 2.2.0 which is a
problem for anyone running a RHEL/CentOS 6 distribution.

Normally this would not be a big deal since we can bump minimum required
versions but in this case simplejson is an optional runtime dependency
so most projects don't list it in their requirements.txt files.  So if
you are running with simplejson < 2.2.0 (you might not even know it) and
upgrade, things are going to get sad very quick.

Rather than assume people will be at the right level or figure it out,
let's be smarter and just check if the kwarg is available in the version
of simplejson we're using.

This can be removed in Kilo when python 2.6 support is dropped so this
should be short-term workaround that saves some headaches once Juno is
released.

Closes-Bug: #1361230

Change-Id: Iadc2d28a1a0b125a34ed08344673c6b4a8a758e9
"}, {'created': '2014-09-03 20:24:39.000000000', 'message': "Check for namedtuple_as_object support before using it

This can be removed in Kilo when python 2.6 support is dropped so this

Closes-Bug: #1361230

commit_message:
Check for namedtuple_as_object support before using it

Commit ad248f6658d572f3f4721f804325db754e9c931d introduced the usage of
the namedtuple_as_object kwarg if using simplejson.

However, that kwarg isn't available until simplejson 2.2.0 which is a
problem for anyone running a RHEL/CentOS 6 distribution.

Normally this would not be a big deal since we can bump minimum required
versions but in this case simplejson is an optional runtime dependency
so most projects don't list it in their requirements.txt files.  So if
you are running with simplejson < 2.2.0 (you might not even know it) and
upgrade, things are going to get sad very quick.

Rather than assume people will be at the right level or figure it out,
let's be smarter and just check if the kwarg is available in the version
of simplejson we're using.  If we don't have a new enough version of
simplejson then fallback to using json despite the performance issues
on python 2.6.

This can be removed in Kilo when python 2.6 support is dropped so this
should be short-term workaround that saves some headaches once Juno is
released.

Closes-Bug: #1361230

Change-Id: Iadc2d28a1a0b125a34ed08344673c6b4a8a758e9

commit_message:
Fix minor nits for token2saml generation.

bknudson left few (mostly) minor comments on the token2saml patch.
This commit addresses them.

Change-Id: I755e4a064d5ada1215e82f143914af1bd1cfcd9d
Implements: bp keystone-to-keystone-federation

So this is an alternative to the command line tool right?'}, {'account_id': 8978, 'date': '2014-08-24 11:06:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Nope!
It'a route so federated SP can specify the route and fetch the metadata, which in fact was generated by a cmd line tool beforehand. If you look at the controller it simply opens the file and returns it with a text/xml header.
Since such metadata is not usually very generic I have decided to serve a static file, which I think will faster than generation metadata on the fly.
AFAIR Dolph agreed on that approach."}, {'account_id': 8978, 'date': '2014-08-25 23:06:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Routes for Keystone-IdP metadata endpoint

Keystone acting as an Identity Provider should expose an endpoint
where federated peers can access its SAML2 Metadata file.

API spec: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/118074/

Change-Id: I94d26ce88d2468af71bc1c9d1cba1b422da4480e
Implements: bp keystone-to-keystone-federation

commit_message:
IdP SAML Metadata generator

Keystone acting as a SAML2 Identity Provider needs to be able to
generate and expose metadata that is consumed by federated
Service Providers.

Co-Authored-By: Steve Martinelli <stevemar@ca.ibm.com>
Change-Id: I9e4b2f068a8190215749b95f31d634eb09c1e3f1
Implements: bp keystone-to-keystone-federation

commit_message:
Combine acc/cont put_* methods and fix their lock problem.

The container backend is supposed to build a pending file and,
when it gets to a certain size, flush it all at once into the
sqlite db. Before this fix, many concurrent threads would ask
what the pending file size is to see if they should flush
instead of just appending to the pending file. The problem is
that many would ask, find it's too big, and try to get a lock.
The first one wins, flushes, but all the other waiting threads
still think they have to flush- which is a much slower opertaion
than just the append. This change gets the lock first and makes
sure that merge_items is only called when the pending file is full.

Change-Id: I29cfa13a48c8f7d16dd414b2288d50461adbafd2

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-29 23:08:16.000000000', 'message': "Fix last_modified_date_to_timestamp on non-UTC systems

Before, we were calling datetime.datetime.strftime('%s.%f') to convert
a datetime to epoch seconds + microseconds. However, the '%s' format
isn't actually part of Python's library. Rather, Python passes that on
to the system C library, which is typically glibc. Now, glibc takes
the '%s' format and helpfully* applies the current timezone as an
offset. This gives bogus results on machines where UTC is not the
system timezone. (Yes, some people really do that.)

For example:

    >>> import os
    >>> from swift.common import utils
    >>> os.environ['TZ'] = 'PST8PDT,M3.2.0,M11.1.0'
    >>> float(utils.last_modified_date_to_timestamp('1970-01-01T00:00:00.000000'))
    28800.0
    >>>

That timestamp should obviously be 0.

This patch replaces the strftime() call with datetime arithmetic,
which is entirely in Python so the system timezone doesn't mess it up.

* unhelpfully

Change-Id: I56855acd79a5d8f2c98a771fa9fd2729e4f490b1
"}, {'created': '2014-08-30 01:34:06.000000000', 'message': "Fix last_modified_date_to_timestamp on non-UTC systems

commit_message:
Fix last_modified_date_to_timestamp on non-UTC systems

Before, we were calling datetime.datetime.strftime('%s.%f') to convert
a datetime to epoch seconds + microseconds. However, the '%s' format
isn't actually part of Python's library. Rather, Python passes that on
to the system C library, which is typically glibc. Now, glibc takes
the '%s' format and helpfully* applies the current timezone as an
offset. This gives bogus results on machines where UTC is not the
system timezone. (Yes, some people really do that.)

For example:

    >>> import os
    >>> from swift.common import utils
    >>> os.environ['TZ'] = 'PST8PDT,M3.2.0,M11.1.0'
    >>> float(utils.last_modified_date_to_timestamp('1970-01-01T00:00:00.000000'))
    28800.0
    >>>

That timestamp should obviously be 0.

This patch replaces the strftime() call with datetime arithmetic,
which is entirely in Python so the system timezone doesn't mess it up.

* unhelpfully

Change-Id: I56855acd79a5d8f2c98a771fa9fd2729e4f490b1

commit_message:
V1.1: Add claim_id to message url

If message is claimed, the returned message href now contains
?claim_id=  part. Also in this commit function for message uri construction
was DRYed and extracted to wsgi.utils module.

Partially-implements: blueprint api-v1.1-response-document-changes
Change-Id: Ic8f1a83dbe11366bad519e6507d074202b2b37dd

commit_message:
Some scenario tests do not delete network resources

The ScenarioTest class does not destroy isolated creds upon tearDown.
As several scenarios create network resources through the class
tempest.common.IsolatedCreds, a missing cleanup results in network
resources not being removed.

(4 comments)

The changes to the container updater need to be reverted. Yes, a container has a storage policy, but the container updater is pushing container info to account servers, so the policy doesn't matter for purposes of quorum. The way it's written now, a container with an RS 10+4 policy will cause the container updater to want to push to 11 account replicas before calling it a success, which is problematic since there are typically only 3 account replicas.

I don't know if I like that change from utils.quorum_size to utils.replication_quorum_size, and I wonder what other reviewers think of it. (Of course, "quit bikeshedding" might be the answer.)'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-28 23:54:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-31 20:10:49.000000000', 'message': "EC: Make quorum_size() specific to storage policy

quorum size ie, the number of successful backend operations,
is used by the proxy to deem the client request serviceable
or successful.  With introduction of non-replication storage
policies, quorum_size definition will depend on the policy
type.  For 'replication' policies, it is a function of the
number of object replicas configured, whereas for the
'erasure_coding' type policies, it is a function of the
number of data fragments the original data was split into.

This patch adds quorum_size() definitions for the currently
supported storage policy (sub)classes:

   ReplicationStoragePolicy and ECStoragePolicy.

for object server.

Storage policies are not supported for account and container
services - the default 'replication' style quorum_size()
definition will continue to apply to those.

Changes:

 - Turn generic quorum_size() into ac_quorum_size() which
   is applicable only to account and container services
 - Define quorum_size() per StoragePolicy type
 - Update callers of quorum_size() to reflect the above change
 - Add quorum_size() unit test code for account, container
   and object servers (taking storage policy into account)

Change-Id: I25fd27267897826194f9babc696f3c371aee4d44
Implements: blueprint ec-proxy-work

commit_message:
EC: Make quorum_size() specific to storage policy

quorum size ie, the number of successful backend operations,
is used by the proxy to deem the client request serviceable
or successful.  With introduction of non-replication storage
policies, quorum_size definition will depend on the policy
type.  For 'replication' policies, it is a function of the
number of object replicas configured, whereas for the
'erasure_coding' type policies, it is a function of the
number of data fragments the original data was split into.

This patch adds quorum_size() definitions for the currently
supported storage policy (sub)classes:

   ReplicationStoragePolicy and ECStoragePolicy.

for object server.

Storage policies are not supported for account and container
services - the default 'replication' style quorum_size()
definition will continue to apply to those.

Changes:

 - Turn generic quorum_size() into replication_quorum_size() which
   is applicable only to account and container services
 - Define quorum_size() per StoragePolicy subclass
 - Return replication_quorum_size() from ReplicationStoragePolicy
 - Consult PyECLib to calculate ECStoragePolicy-specific quorum size
 - Update callers of quorum_size() to reflect the above change
 - Add quorum_size() unit test code for account, container
   and object servers (taking storage policy into account)

Change-Id: I25fd27267897826194f9babc696f3c371aee4d44
Implements: blueprint ec-proxy-work

It is a little optimization of describe function. If there wasn't found any

commit_message:
Avoid to iterate over empty list in DictMismatch

It is a little optimization of describe function. If there wasn't found any
differences, there is loop iterating over empty list. It isn't necessary,
because condition a few lines above do the same.

Change-Id: I65067801281c8703f7fa4d1430dcc578d28c3542

[{'created': '2014-08-13 21:18:33.000000000', 'message': 'Make floatingip-ip-delete atomic with neutron

The infra guys were noticing an issue where they were leaking floating ip
addresses. One of the reasons this would occur for them is they called
nova floating-ip-delete which first disassocates the floating-ip in neutron
and then deletes it. Because nova-api makes two calls to neutron if the
first one succeeds and the second fails it results in the instance no longer
being associated with the floatingip. They have retry logic but they base it on
the instance and when they go to retry cleaning up the instance the floatingip
is no longer on the instance so they never delete it.

This patch fixes this issue by creating a new method disassocate_and_delete
which contains the different logic needed to atomically do this for neutron
rather than putting the logic in the api layer to do something differently
if one is using neutron.

This patch also adds additional code coverage for nova-network in the
delete floatingip case.

Closes-bug: 1356157

Conflicts:
	nova/api/openstack/compute/contrib/floating_ips.py
	nova/network/base_api.py
	nova/network/neutronv2/api.py

Change-Id: I53b0c9d949404288e8687b304361a74b53d69ef3

commit_message:
Make floatingip-ip-delete atomic with neutron

The infra guys were noticing an issue where they were leaking floating ip
addresses. One of the reasons this would occur for them is they called
nova floating-ip-delete which first disassocates the floating-ip in neutron
and then deletes it. Because nova-api makes two calls to neutron if the
first one succeeds and the second fails it results in the instance no longer
being associated with the floatingip. They have retry logic but they base it on
the instance and when they go to retry cleaning up the instance the floatingip
is no longer on the instance so they never delete it.

This patch fixes this issue by creating a new method
disassocate_and_delete_floating_ip which contains the different logic
needed to atomically do this for neutron rather than putting the logic
in the api layer to do something differently if one is using neutron.

This patch also adds additional code coverage for nova-network in the
delete floatingip case.

Closes-bug: 1356157

Conflicts:
	nova/api/openstack/compute/contrib/floating_ips.py
	nova/network/base_api.py

Change-Id: I53b0c9d949404288e8687b304361a74b53d69ef3
(cherry picked from commit 5f391087d1d75dd4e7532252c312256e9c3ea2b9)

[{'created': '2014-09-05 00:08:57.000000000', 'message': "Fix race condition with vif plugging in finish migrate

The tempest test that does a resize on an instance from time to time fails
with neutron with a virtual interface timout error. The reason why this
occurs is that nova-compute calls a vifs_unplug() then vifs_plug() fairly
quickly and the neutron-agent doesn't realize this happens because the way
it detects this is via polling. This patch fixings this problem by passing
vifs_already_plugged=True to _create_domain_and_network to avoid waiting
for the neutron notifcation.

Initially, I thought this problem could be solved by setting
vifs_already_plugged=True if migrate.source_host == migrate_desk.dest_host
but it turns out that this race condition can still occur if migrated to
another host though it's fairly unlikely. Always setting
vifs_already_plugged=True ensures we never hit this issue on migrate.

Change-Id: I90424ad50ac993c4abb049aa0654a94b225b5ebb
Closes-bug: 1357599
Closes-bug: 1357476
(cherry picked from commit 80deed660815b9ba69e424b83805a21768b02bb6)
"}]
commit_message:
Fix race condition with vif plugging in finish migrate

The tempest test that does a resize on an instance from time to time fails
with neutron with a virtual interface timout error. The reason why this
occurs is that nova-compute calls a vifs_unplug() then vifs_plug() fairly
quickly and the neutron-agent doesn't realize this happens because the way
it detects this is via polling. This patch fixings this problem by passing
vifs_already_plugged=True to _create_domain_and_network to avoid waiting
for the neutron notifcation.

Initially, I thought this problem could be solved by setting
vifs_already_plugged=True if migrate.source_host == migrate_desk.dest_host
but it turns out that this race condition can still occur if migrated to
another host though it's fairly unlikely. Always setting
vifs_already_plugged=True ensures we never hit this issue on migrate.

Change-Id: I90424ad50ac993c4abb049aa0654a94b225b5ebb
Closes-bug: 1357599
Closes-bug: 1357476
(cherry picked from commit 80deed660815b9ba69e424b83805a21768b02bb6)

commit_message:
Fix load balancer scenario if no tenant network

The load balancer scenario is currently dependent on isolated
tenant networking.  This updates it to allow it to pass in environments
where tenant networking is not present (ie, a shared cross-tenant network).
If a network cannot be resolved by tenant, it will be resolved by the
configured private network name as a fallback and its associated subnet
will be used.

Change-Id: Idbac7c10669a0e2db518223cdd762313aa752876
(cherry picked from commit 3e9e99fb7d7c43b5a6340919f4f1f611f387cbbb)

commit_message:
Fix missing trailing commas for modal dialogs

Trailing commas were accidentally removed from the 'classes' attribute
of the table actions for the Create Property and the Create Volume Type
Extra Spec dialogs. This caused the dialogs to lose the modality.

This submit fixes the problem on the two dialogs.

Change-Id: Id2c2d1f8354e95016dc121d1143a6ea5b4460de1
Closes-Bug: #1362704

commit_message:
Capitalize all instances of Keystone in the docs

There were quite a few instances of `keystone` where `Keystone`
should have been used. Code examples were not changed, since that
would break things.

Change-Id: I533ad1b71cc3af1b70bb54cca0a820aaad3f62da

[{'created': '2014-09-04 19:09:28.000000000', 'message': "Only log console log if nova supports consoles

If a scenario test fails during ssh the standard procedure is to log
the console for the server. However, this can only be done if nova
supports consoles. This commit adds a check to see if nova supports
getting the console for a server before it attempts to do it.
Otherwise if nova doesn't support getting the console and an ssh
connection fails the test will fail on getting a console and not the
ssh connection. It looks like this check wasn't added during the
scenario test port to the tempest clients.

Change-Id: I681b3065d86cd31837a9ef5d91d25847fa47a8f4
"}]
commit_message:
Only log console log if nova supports consoles

If a scenario test fails during ssh the standard procedure is to log
the console for the server. However, this can only be done if nova
supports consoles. This commit adds a check to see if nova supports
getting the console for a server before it attempts to do it.
Otherwise if nova doesn't support getting the console and an ssh
connection fails the test will fail on getting a console and not the
ssh connection. It looks like this check wasn't added during the
scenario test port to the tempest clients.

Change-Id: I681b3065d86cd31837a9ef5d91d25847fa47a8f4

For restore from LVM volumes to work, the restore must be done
on the host that serves the volume, since local_path is used

Change-Id: Iad1fb5588b8365a0a165754389340bca3f1830b5
Closes-Bug: #1365065

commit_message:
During a restore send the restore request to the right host

For restore from LVM volumes to work, the restore must be done
on the host that serves the volume, since local_path is used
in the restore code.

Change-Id: Iad1fb5588b8365a0a165754389340bca3f1830b5
Closes-Bug: #1365065

Provide the hotref sphinx extension

This extension simplifies the generation of hyperlinks referencing HOT
resources in the hot-reference book. It will be used in the hot-guide.

Implements: blueprint heat-templates

commit_message:
Remove SELECT FOR UPDATE use in delete_firewall

SELECT FOR UPDATE expression, which is triggered with the use of the
SQLAlchemy Query object's with_lockmode('update') method, is
detrimental to performance and scalability of the database
performance code in Neutron due to the lock contention it produces.

SELECT FOR UPDATE can be entirely avoided in delete_firewall method
with the use of single-shot DELETE expressions.

Partial-Bug: #1364358
Change-Id: Ia8db73312f5dff6a5bd573694a60a798279834cb

commit_message:
Remove unused arg to config.setup_logging()

The cfg.CFG argument is ignored and misleading.  This change removes it
and updates all callers.

Closes-Bug: #1355565
Change-Id: I2fcece85d1abe848e5c01125cfb62c02f2dcbc86

commit_message:
Minor change to neutron controller script

Moves nova related parameter to its respective location, does not
have any functional impacts. Also swaps auth_protocol with auth_port
to keep it in sync with install guides. Classifies ml2 sections by
adding comments.

Change-Id: I7739451f2959099e2b9485b2e0adbe721a9edfd7

commit_message:
Remove unused dependency on oslo.config

Nothing in oslo.utils imports oslo.config, so don't list it as a
requirement for installation.

Change-Id: I16e68df8b01ac84bb08227b2bd3d8a81dcf34d76

commit_message:
Fixes a mock cleanup issue caused by oslotest

The latest olsotest includes a call the mock.patch.stopall. If a patch's
stop is registered as a cleanup before oslotest add its cleanup the
following traceback will happen:

    local/lib/python2.7/site-packages/mock.py", line 1376, in __exit__
        raise RuntimeError('stop called on unstarted patcher')
    RuntimeError: stop called on unstarted patcher

This is because the cleanups are handled by testtools in reverse and by
the time our cleanup runs the patch would have already been cleaned up.

Change-Id: I6df0a267420eec794582acdf0429a141e7f64e45
Partial-Bug: #1365678

commit_message:
Fix logging config twice

The config was being logged twice, once from keystone-all and once
from keystone.openstack.common.service. The logging done by
keystone-all is removed.

Change-Id: I7af03fb9db819b0ee21953988271c42ec8aa3c7a
Closes-Bug: #1363709

commit_message:
install test-reqs when TESTONLY packages are installed

INSTALL_TESTONLY_PACKAGES in devstack only impacts .deb/.rpm files
even though most of our test requirements are actually specified
in python. This will do an explicit install of test-requirements.txt
if pip_install is called with args that look like a directory,
and test-requirements.txt exists in that directory.

Change-Id: Id21e282ddc945c819c9c8c4d724658e28bfde785

commit_message:
Make Identity client load like the others

This does a couple of things:
* Loads the Identity client module in the same manner as the other
  'base' clients (where 'base' == 'included in the OSC repo')
* Changes the entry point group name for the base clients to
  'openstack.cli.base'.  The extension group name remains the same.
* Loads the base modules first followed by the extension modules.
  This load order ensures that the extension module commands are all
  loaded _after_ the base commands, allowing extensions to now override
  the base commands.

Change-Id: I4b9ca7f1df6eb8bbe8e3f663f3065c2ed80ce20b

I'm a -1 on this because the implementation here is different from the libvirt one (and hence the overall concept) in two significant ways:

1) The change doesn't make use of the retry_interval, which was added because depending on the state of GuestOS a single APCI request can be missed (the typical case for hitting this is if the VM is still booting and not yet ready to shutdown.  Its no clear from the patch how hyperV is handling this situation - in fact it looks from the comments in the exception handler of _soft_shutdown() that the hyperv driver will simply log a warning and abort the shutdown in this case, which doesn't seem the right thing to do 

2) In this change if the soft shutdown fails in the timeout period the VM state seems to be updated to HYPERV_VM_STATE_DISABLED (not sure if this actual has any effect on the state seen by Nova), whereas the expected behaviour is that a hard shutdown is performed instead.

On that basis (and I freely admit that my hyperv knowledge is very limited) this patch seems to be implementing different behaviour, which is generally not allowed across different hypervisors.   Happy to be corrected or otherwise convinced by the hyperv experts though.

Phil"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-01 14:00:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

commit_message:
Adds Hyper-V soft shutdown implementation

This commit gives the Hyper-V guest VMs a chance to
shutdown gracefully within a time limit, doing a
hard shutdown if they fail to do so.

Partially-Implements: blueprint user-defined-shutdown

Change-Id: I68361ab43d8bba96af063b2ec53f89833a30d02a
