commit_message:
Convert rescue v3 plugin to v2.1 API

Changes required to have v3 plugin natively support the V2.1
API.

The parameters admin_password and image_ref were reverted to
adminPass and rescue_image_ref

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api
Co-Authored-By: Chris Yeoh <cyeoh@au1.ibm.com>
Change-Id: Ibca991b5d6ec065ea9fbb0318c4ab51a3c5a3eba

[{'created': '2014-08-02 18:20:56.000000000', 'message': "Glance Metadata Definitions Catalog

Implements: blueprint metadata-schema-catalog

A common API hosted by the Glance service for vendors, admins,
services, and users to meaningfully define available key / value
pair and tag metadata. The intent is to enable better metadata
collaboration across artifacts, services, and projects for
OpenStack users.

This is about the definition of the available metadata that can
be used on different types of resources (images, artifacts,
volumes, flavors, aggregates, etc). A definition includes the
properties type, its key, it's description, and it's constraints.
This catalogue will not store the values for specific instance
properties.

WORK IN PROGRESS

 - Seed Data

Change-Id: Ib1c1abf80879fb6dcd5ee30c7d2bc65b0ba720d5

commit_message:
Glance Metadata Definitions Catalog - Seed

Implements: blueprint metadata-schema-catalog

A common API hosted by the Glance service for vendors, admins,
services, and users to meaningfully define available key / value
pair and tag metadata. The intent is to enable better metadata
collaboration across artifacts, services, and projects for
OpenStack users.

This is about the definition of the available metadata that can
be used on different types of resources (images, artifacts,
volumes, flavors, aggregates, etc). A definition includes the
properties type, its key, it's description, and it's constraints.
This catalogue will not store the values for specific instance
properties.

Change-Id: Ib1c1abf80879fb6dcd5ee30c7d2bc65b0ba720d5
DocImpact
Co-Authored-By: Lakshmi N Sampath <lakshmi.sampath@hp.com>
Co-Authored-By: Wayne Okuma <wayne.okuma@hp.com>
Co-Authored-By: Travis Tripp <travis.tripp@hp.com>
Co-Authored-By: Pawel Koniszewski <pawel.koniszewski@intel.com>
Co-Authored-By: Michal Jastrzebski <michal.jastrzebski@intel.com>
Co-Authored-By: Michal Dulko <michal.dulko@intel.com>

Hey,

I just left some comments in both driver and controller modules. It's getting better, however, I think there's a bit of mixed up logic in some parts.

For example, it's not clear to me what parts actually belong to the driver, what parts belong to the eventloop and what other pats belong to pyngus. To be more precise, there are some callbacks like `connection_failed` that are being called from the _SocketConncetion instance and I wonder whether that logic should go into pyngus or not.

One more thing, the driver, especially the controller, seems to ask a lot for permission instead of forgiveness. I've nothing against that but I'm really concerned about unforeseen failures/exceptions that should be used as a landing pad to call callbacks etc."}, {'account_id': 1247, 'date': '2014-07-02 11:52:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Hi Flavio,

Thanks for the feedback - I've pushed up another patchset that I think addresses most of the points you raised.

I've tried to simplify the callback logic a bit.  I agree with your last comment regarding the use of the 'connection-failed" callback.  This is a callback that is used by Pyngus to signal a protocol-level failure of the connection.  The eventloop.py/_SocketConnection code was also leveraging that callback for handling socket failures, since in the end the same actions needed to be performed.

I've moved the socket failures into their own callback, separate from the protocol error callback used by pyngus in the latest patch.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-02 21:48:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Verified-1

This patch is an update against the current master branch.  It includes a few fixes for issues Gordon and I have found while doing some perf testing.

Note well: Pypi now includes the proton python wrappers.  This new package includes a C extension that is built when the package is installed.  In order to build&install this package, you'll need to have the Proton C development libraries installed locally.   These can be installed from EPEL (qpid-proton-c-devel) for rhel-based systems.  Packages have also been proposed for debian, but have yet to be included in that distro.  There's a PPA available for Ubuntu 14 LTS otherwise (ppa:qpid/released)."}, {'account_id': 8770, 'date': '2014-07-25 15:22:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 12:

In reply to Alexei's feedback:

> Alexei Kornienko		Jul 9 3:26 PM
> 
> Patch Set 11: Code-Review-1
> 
> This driver doesn't respect flow defined by MessagingServer. Cause of this I think that it should implement it's own messaging server (since it's using it's own controller and main loop).

Thanks for the feedback Alexei.  You're correct, currently the driver's ability to back pressure senders in inadequate.  This especially affects the 'cast' pattern, which lacks the explicit backpressure of an rpc that waits for a reply.

Gordon and I have been working on changes to the way the driver grants credit on behalf of subscribers, as well as changes that will backpressure senders based on available credit.

I haven't made much progress in the area to date - I've been focusing on trying to get CI/devstack/gate support for this driver in place as that seems to be a major block to getting this driver included upstream.  My plan was to open a bug for the credit work after I put something in place for CI/devstack/gate."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-25 15:32:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12: Verified-1

(2 comments)

Couple of nits.

I think we need to agree on what to do with this driver.

I'm not really happy about this driver landing without a proper gate but I know the patches are up for review and there's commitment on making that happen. The driver won't reach a perfect state until we merge it and let people give it a try. Furthermore, at the Juno summit, we had a session on this driver and some benchmarks and live-tests results were presented.

What I'm getting at is that I'd be happy to let this driver land as-is if we get full commitment from Ken on making the gate thing happen asap.

This patch has been around since Icehouse. We either let it land as-is or block it until all the gates are setup, which probably means L (not even Kilo). Lets agree on something before the feature freeze.

Just out of curiosity why is this being put into oslo.messaging?

Kombu now has a qpid driver, why not put it in kombu so it can be used in a more general purpose manner by entities outside openstack?

If the question was already raised let me know, but it seems like we should (imho) be contributing to libraries that are general purpose, not contributing to libraries that are only useful in openstack (and really are only useful in openstack applications...)

Thoughts?

Maybe I should raise this on the ML instead since it might involve others that want to have some input; something just doesn't seem right when we are duplicating (and thus having to maintain) things that are better served by other open solutions..."}, {'account_id': 8784, 'date': '2014-09-01 09:22:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 17:

> Just out of curiosity why is this being put into
> oslo.messaging?
>
> Kombu now has a qpid driver, why not put it in kombu so
> it can be used in a more general purpose manner by
> entities outside openstack?

This is intended to be an AMQP 1.0 (ISO/IEC 19464) driver, with a clean and well defined mapping to the protocol.

It is not intended as a qpid specific driver. There already is one of those for oslo.messaging. It uses an older version of AMQP superceded by 1.0 (as does the qpid support in kombu, I believe). Though anyone wanting to use qpidd could do so using this new driver (which I believe will perform and scale much better than the existing qpid specific one), this driver is intended to be of much wider use.

The wire protocol becomes an interface, that when honoured allows different solutions at deployment. (The pre-1.0 iterations of AMQP are really entirely different protocols).

> If the question was already raised let me know, but it
> seems like we should (imho) be contributing to libraries
> that are general purpose, not contributing to libraries
> that are only useful in openstack (and really are only
> useful in openstack applications...)

I'm not sure I understand your point here. The oslo.messaging library itself is only used in openstack. As I understand it, it is intended as a pluggable RPC+notify model that is actually implemented over other messaging technologies, through different drivers. This is such a driver, whose aim is to provide AMQP 1.0 protocol support to users of oslo.messaging. 

Are you saying you don't think oslo.messaging should be pluggable in this way? That it should just use kombu and whatever that offers?

If so, the problem I see with that is that the kombu model and API is really driven by a specific older version of AMQP (0-9-1). Using it to drive other protocols obscures the mapping, may prevent access to useful features and  impact the efficiency of use. The oslo.messaging library itself offers a slightly higher level abstraction (rpc & notify) and I believe adapting that to different solutions gives more flexibility and is more likely to offer real choice by allowing different technologies supported to be fully exploited to the best of their capabilities.

> Thoughts?
> 
> Maybe I should raise this on the ML instead since it
> might involve others that want to have some input;
> something just doesn't seem right when we are duplicating
> (and thus having to maintain) things that are better 
> served by other open solutions...

I don't think anything is being duplicated by this driver. As above the qpid support in kombu and the existing qpid driver could be considered to be overlapping. This driver however is offering a completely different protocol."}, {'account_id': 7536, 'date': '2014-09-01 15:36:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 17: Code-Review-1

(10 comments)'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2014-09-01 20:51:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 17:

I'm not saying much either way.

I just wanted to hear the opinions and see the feedback so that at least someone asked the obvious (at least I think it's obvious) question about helping kombu become more capable instead of just helping oslo.messaging (which is a big user of kombu) become better (even if kombu may not be the perfect API match at the current moment).

It just feels like we have taken a lot from kombu and how much have we given back? That's all..."}, {'account_id': 8770, 'date': '2014-09-02 16:21:15.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 18.'}, {'account_id': 8770, 'date': '2014-09-02 16:21:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 17:

'}, {'created': '2014-07-02 20:58:05.000000000', 'message': 'An initial implementation of a 1.0 based messaging driver

This driver uses the Pyngus module, which is a client API built on the
Proton AMQP 1.0 protocol engine library from the Apache Qpid project.

The key driver interfaces are implemented in the ProtonDriver class in
driver.py.  The logic for interfacing with Pyngus in order to
send/receive messages, manage AMQP connections and links, and handle
protocol events is in controller.py.  eventloop.py is a fairly generic
socket connection and I/O processor which runs in its own thread.
controller.py uses the eventloop.py thread to schedule subscription
and message send requests from the driver, as well as handle all
protocol event callbacks coming from Pyngus.

Included in this patch are a set of functional tests that can be run
under tox (tox -eamqp1).  These tests fully exercise the new driver,
from the driver API down to the 'wire' - nothing in the driver is
mocked out.  The functional tests implement a simple loopback test
broker, which allows the driver to send and receive messages via the
local network.  All RPC call patterns, RPC timeouts, and even broker
failover are verified by the included functional tests.

This driver uses the Pyngus module, which is a pure-python client API
built on the Proton AMQP 1.0 protocol engine library from the Apache
Qpid project.  Pyngus is available via pypi.python.org.

This driver introduces a dependency on the Proton AMQP 1.0 protocol
library, which is a platform-dependent library that must be installed
in order to use this driver and run the functional tests.

commit_message:
An initial implementation of an AMQP 1.0 based messaging driver

The key driver interfaces are implemented in the ProtonDriver class in
driver.py.  The logic for interfacing with Pyngus in order to
send/receive messages, manage AMQP connections and links, and handle
protocol events is in controller.py.  eventloop.py is a fairly generic
socket connection and I/O processor which runs in its own thread.
controller.py uses the eventloop.py thread to schedule subscription
and message send requests from the driver, as well as handle all
protocol event callbacks coming from Pyngus.

Included in this patch are a set of functional tests that can be run
under tox (tox -eamqp1).  These tests fully exercise the new driver,
from the driver API down to the 'wire' - nothing in the driver is
mocked out.  The functional tests implement a simple loopback test
broker, which allows the driver to send and receive messages via the
local network.  All RPC call patterns, RPC timeouts, and even broker
failover are verified by the included functional tests.

This driver uses the Pyngus module, which is a pure-python client API
built on the Proton AMQP 1.0 protocol engine library from the Apache
Qpid project.  Pyngus is available via pypi.python.org.

This driver introduces a dependency on the Proton AMQP 1.0 protocol
library, which is a platform-dependent library that must be installed
in order to use this driver and run the functional tests.

Change-Id: I871703e4cdc04cee3e6c214e911c9df464ede2ed
Implements: blueprint amqp10-driver-implementation

commit_message:
Add API schema for v2.1/v3 server_metadata API

By defining the API schema, it is possible to separate the validation
code from the API method. The API method can be more simple.
In addition, a response of API validation error can be consistent for
the whole Nova API.

Partially implements blueprint v3-api-schema

Change-Id: I4ef7d71f5d8eba13535f2c1a4aaf2b1f8d73a922

commit_message:
virt: add method get_serial_console to driver

Adds get_serial_console that returns a typed object with
all necessary information to connect to the instance.

Co-Authored-By: Ian Wells <iawells@cisco.com>
Co-Authored-By: Sushma Korati <sushma_korati@persistent.co.in>
Co-Authored-By: Sahid Orentino Ferdjaoui <sahid.ferdjaoui@redhat.com>

Partial-Implements: blueprint serial-ports
Change-Id: Idc3ed6f3a8cf561c8fb7ac3cf600dbad96c4f662

commit_message:
Move to epel 7-1 release

EPEL7 has updated.  AFAIK there is no better way to determine this; we
could possibly scrape [1] but this just seems to replace one problem
with another (maintaining the scraping)

[1] http://download.fedoraproject.org/pub/epel/7/x86_64/repoview/epel-release.html

Change-Id: Iadf66c92fcf31edeb0f364a5b1de5d87630e9a42

commit_message:
Add API schema for v2.1/v3 multiple_create extension

By defining the API schema, it is possible to separate the validation
code from the API method. The API method can be more simple.
In addition, a response of API validation error can be consistent for
the whole Nova API.

Partially implements blueprint v3-api-schema

Change-Id: Ibf0b6a5024f834ac9252933568d4416a8a5ba1fc

commit_message:
Update the HP 3PAR default persona

The HP 3PAR drivers was setting the default persona to Generic.
The default should actually be Generic-ALUA for Linux based host.

DocImpact
This will require an update in the OpenStack Configuration Reference
Guide under the supported operations page for the HP 3PAR drivers.
The new default for the hp3par:persona should be '2 - Generic-ALUA'.

Change-Id: I65860a0b58f52ead0c86a0f0ab9a9ad755f76e72

commit_message:
Use create_process() instead of execute() in find_child_pids()

If AsyncProcess is used with root_helper then last search for child pid
in the process hierarchy produces unwanted error to logs. This error is
expected since last child in hierarchy doesn't have any child processes.

Change-Id: I24e118742656cbd0445a1e31d7e0110f1ab34f31
Related-Bug: 1243216

commit_message:
Deny updates to AWS::EC2::VolumeAttachment

In accordance with AWS docs [1] AWS VolumeAttachment does not support
updates of any of its properties.

[1] http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/aws-properties-ec2-ebs-volumeattachment.html

Change-Id: I6d79536c68bed60d9b86c662147e35a9b2da6c1c
Closes-Bug: #1340096

commit_message:
Improve structure of external_gateway_added

There is no functional change in this patch.  However, this refactor
allows another patch [1] to make a simpler change to the code base.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/112146/

Related-bug: #1353006

IPv4 addresses still validate as before, only now IPv6 addresses validate as well. I highly doubt that anyone would like to disallow ipv6 hosts from being specified in their mysql privilege settings.

Nikhil, could you please comment on this?

I disagree with the premise of this change for two primary reasons.

The first is marked as inline comments on the code (models.py).

The other is that the sense of the config value is being changed. "Require IPv4" isn't the same as "Require valid IP". How exactly to handle this, I'm not sure but one thought is to have a require valid ipv6 and a require valid IP; two new options.

Use those in address validation.

These are my opinions. The code works, it does no worse than the old one. So I'm not rating this a -1.'}, {'account_id': 2340, 'date': '2014-09-02 13:51:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

commit_message:
allow both ipv4 and ipv6 hostnames by default

Refactored the code to use netaddr rather than re-implementing IP
address validation. This gives us IPv6 support for free.

DocImpact
The hostname_require_ipv4 configuration option is being
removed in favor of hostname_require_valid_ip. The latter is more
inclusive and validates both IPv4 and IPv6 addresses.

Change-Id: I36c76169f2ab3bb7f54f67db522309a49ae61f7a
Closes-Bug: #1343192

commit_message:
Add API schema for v2.1/v3 availability_zone extension

By defining the API schema, it is possible to separate the validation
code from the API method. The API method can be more simple.
In addition, a response of API validation error can be consistent for
the whole Nova API.

Partially implements blueprint v3-api-schema

Change-Id: I4a7bd2ef4df322eb072730bbf7da2766f02cb398

commit_message:
Replace @example.com in OpenStack service users

The fix for bug 1362173 replaced @mirantis.com addresses
with @example.com addresses. Those should have been
replaced with @localhost addresses in order to maintain
consistency with other services address, as well as
preventing the services from potentially spamming
@example.com.

Change-Id: Ib10d64317ae162b00288630b37f57576490a5939

commit_message:
Set configs for glance_store

glance_store uses a new section to keep its configs. This patch
duplicates the existing, store related, config options and sets them
under the glance_store section.

Once glance is fully migrated, the old options will be removed.

Change-Id: Ie3de87cf07a321415d111e644ccbb360c7491151

commit_message:
Add OpenStack HA issues to Resolved Issues

038-resolved-ha-issues -- a separate section for the OpenStack HA
bugs resolved in 5.1.

Description for 1340567 needs rewrite to reflect recent activity
on the bug

Patch 1 contains two of these issues, arranged as a bullet list
under "Resolved Issues".  I don't think that presentation is
effective but you can review it there.

Change-Id: Ifca5df65a1b4a2fecafd632a2b84adbabda11ecb

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-26 09:15:53.000000000', 'message': 'Don't spawn metadata-proxy for non-isolated nets

If the configuation option "enable_isolated_metadata = True" for the
DHCP agent is set, the neutron-ns-metadata-proxy process is spawned
for all networks, regardless if they are isolated or not. In case
the network is not isolated (ie. connected to a neutron router), the
L3 agent also spawns a proxy process, and the DHCP's proxy is left
unused. This patch adds a check prior to the spawning of new proxies:
if a network is not isolated, no proxy is spawned.

Change-Id: I9bdb8c3d37997b22435bca33ec47a67db08efa51
Closes-bug: #1361545

commit_message:
Don't spawn metadata-proxy for non-isolated nets

If the configuation option "enable_isolated_metadata = True" for the
DHCP agent is set, the neutron-ns-metadata-proxy process is spawned
for all networks, regardless if they are isolated or not. In case
the network is not isolated (ie. connected to a neutron router), the
L3 agent also spawns a proxy process, and the DHCP's proxy is left
unused. This patch adds a check prior to the spawning of new proxies:
if a network is not isolated, no proxy is spawned.

Change-Id: I9bdb8c3d37997b22435bca33ec47a67db08efa51
Closes-bug: #1361545

commit_message:
Adds list_instance_uuids to the Hyper-V driver

In case of large number of servers, the _destroy_evacuated_instances
fails randomly. Implementing list_instance_uuids solves the issue.

Co-Authored-By: Robert Tingirica <rtingirica@cloudbasesolutions.com>
Co-Authored-By: Ionut Balutoiu <ibalutoiu@cloudbasesolutions.com>
Change-Id: I9c58168c012b342bb5dfa0c62a7c39a327f442b3
Closes-bug: #1291364

commit_message:
Fix "Check to see if we are already running DevStack" check

commit d3bf9bdbda9acab17223cf25dd0a2b83b96db522 broke the check
as the check uses SCREEN_NAME, which is not available until
sourcing stackrc.

Closes-Bug: #1365827
Change-Id: I7ccb69fb92290c218a3d581e688694a372985c78

commit_message:
Improved error logging in nova-network for allocate_fixed_ip()

When a Nova deployment runs out of fixed IP addresses, it prints
a stacktrace in the error log, with no clear explanation.

This patch writes the appropriate error message to the log file
which will help deployers identify this issue easily.

Change-Id: I996af666592bf3f4ce15e0a1fcffcc67f4eb2c79
Closes-Bug: #1218572

This is not the first time this change is merged.
We did it with: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/90427/ and then had to revert it with https://review.openstack.org/#/c/97245/.

That was because it unleashed a lot of ssh protocol banner errors!
There is a chance that this was because we did not had yet soft shutdown and abrupt power off right after ssh started could have caused the guest files system to not be in a correct state.

However, I think it will be good to spin this patch a few times (say 7 at least as failure rate for the full job is at 17% for this particular cause)'}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2014-09-05 06:51:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Verify network connectivity before state check

This commit adds an initial ssh connection after bringing a server up
in setUp. This should ensure that the image has a chance to initialize
prior to messing with it's state. The test's here are to verify that
after performing a nova operation on a running instance network
connectivity is retained. However, it's is never checked that we can
connect to the server in the first place. A probable cause for the
constant ssh failures in these tests is that the server hasn't had a
finish it's cloud-init (or cirros-init) stage when we're stopping it,
this should also fix those issues.

Change-Id: I126fd4943582c4b759b3cc5a67babaa8d062fb4d
Partial-Bug: #1349617

    Since backup volume operation and volume/snapshot always use different storage back-end, I have add an config item backup_gigabytes to control project's backup capacity instead of directly using gigabytes.

Test result:
    ?Pass Jenkins? Test and wait other CIs' result.

Two issues:

1) I'm not understanding the purpose of no_backup_gb_quota - see question inline

2) If the backup fails, we aren't unwinding the quota until the error state backup is deleted. Do volumes in error count against quota? I honestly can't remember how that ended up being decided"}, {'account_id': 8874, 'date': '2014-08-27 14:10:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 29:

Volume backup quota is consist of backup number and backup gigabytes.


If config item no_backup_gb_quota = True, it use backup number and backup gigabytes to control backup quota.
If config item no_backup_gb_quota = False, it use  only backup  number to control backup quota.
Config item no_backup_gb_quota works like no_snapshot_gb_quota .


Volumes in error status count against quota, because quota reserve and quota commit operation are finished in cinder-api.'}, {'account_id': 8874, 'date': '2014-08-27 14:13:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 29:

[{'created': '2014-08-02 07:41:53.000000000', 'message': 'Support Volume Backup Quota

Since quota take volumes, snapshots and gigabytes into account, it also
needs to take backup into account.
1. Backup create API is not admin interface, users of projects could
create any number of backups.
2. If some evil users create many more big backups to exhaust the free
space of backup storage-backend, it would cause cinder-backup in the state
of rejecting service.
Based on these two points, I think it is necessary to support volume
backup quota.

blueprint support-volume-backup-quota

commit_message:
Support Volume Backup Quota

Since quota take volumes, snapshots and gigabytes into account, it also
needs to take backup into account.
1. Backup create API is not admin interface, users of projects could
create any number of backups.
2. If some evil users create many more big backups to exhaust the free
space of backup storage-backend, it would cause cinder-backup in the state
of rejecting service.
Based on these two points, I think it is necessary to support volume
backup quota.

blueprint support-volume-backup-quota

Change-Id: Idd24ad2e8a5507bf18e90bd5fad59a4af1c158c6

commit_message:
Sync Kombu Reconnect Patch from Oslo

When reconnecting to a RabbitMQ cluster with mirrored queues in
use, the attempt to release the connection can hang "indefinitely"
somewhere deep down in Kombu.  Blocking the thread for a bit
prior to release seems to kludge around the problem where it is
otherwise reproduceable.

(2 comments)

This is actually quite a bit more than I was expecting for a 'skeleton'. I'm assuming you're basically importing a template here?

I also see a bunch of 'common' stuff for openstack in general. How often does this get updated (ie. how often are we going to need to manually rebase that?)

Also:  I'm not really liking the name 'network_shim' since a 'shim' in my mind is a temporary measure to wedge something in place until a better solution can be found. I changed the name of this to 'network driver' in the latest design docs to signify this will almost certainly be a permanent part of Octavia. Could we rename that directory here?"}, {'account_id': 11685, 'date': '2014-08-30 00:56:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Also, 'node' is a rather over-used term--  as we discussed in IRC, can't se use a more descriptive term for what it is?  (I'm still in favor of 'appliance' as my top choice, as that would clearly indicated that stuff having to do with the load balancing appliance / Octavia VM / container is supposed to go.)"}, {'account_id': 11685, 'date': '2014-08-30 01:09:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Ok, given the number of things we have named 'Node' in the models being defined in other reviews, I suppose it's not unreasonable to leave the directory here named 'node'.  Within the context of this project it should be more obvious.

Should I rename 'Octavia VM' to 'Octavia Node' in the diagram and design docs?"}, {'account_id': 10980, 'date': '2014-08-30 01:13:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

(2 comments)

It's a skeleton, plus the published method for import oslo-incubator (surprised me too), plus a cherry pick of a few pieces in common use.

network_shim -> network_driver, sure.

not using node...  I'm fine with many other things (I had this as VM before; I think I like container the most.)  I just need to hear what folks want.

I'd hold off renaming the docs until we get some consensus."}, {'account_id': 10980, 'date': '2014-08-30 01:24:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

Don't merge until we resolve the naming concerns."}, {'account_id': 11685, 'date': '2014-08-30 01:49:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

Agreed on holding off on updating the docs until we get consensus on the directory name.  FWIW, 'container' is fine by me too.

One thing maybe to keep in mind: With Octavia v2, there's going to be a 'layer-4 router' entity, the reference implementation for which is likely to be another Nova VM running LVS (obviously not the most performant solution we could choose, but a good place to start). There will more than likely be similar image building scripts and other hooey going into it (ie. when we get there, we'll be creating another directory for it).  It'll be similar, but filling a different role than the 'octavia VM' in my docs or the 'container' here.

Anyway, just food for thought, I guess, since we might be setting a precedent with this folder name.

Eesh. (Man, naming things can be hard. :P )"}, {'account_id': 6951, 'date': '2014-08-30 06:16:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

(1 comment)

Really the top problems I have with container and appliance for names is not a big problem.  I just like names that accurately describe what they are referencing, and they are short.  Container and appliance are not that short, which is why I liked node and device.

The only reason node is in the migration and models is because I wanted to get that out for comments.  I knew it was a possibility it will be changed and that will be easy.

I hate naming things, and I'm terrible at it.  Container or application is fine by me (though I don't think they fit as well as device or node, but thats a losing battle)"}, {'account_id': 11685, 'date': '2014-08-30 10:08:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 10750, 'date': '2014-09-02 16:03:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Here are several more options:

octavia/tactic
octavia/strategy
octavia/mechanism

and a few more...

octavia/gizmo
octavia/gadget

I am leaning towards octavia/strategy.'}, {'account_id': 11302, 'date': '2014-09-02 20:19:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Do we have a vote going for a couple different choices? 

I kinda like the name device over container or vm.

First thing I think when hearing container is lxc or the like. Device seems to fit better IMO. 

The load balancer container will contain these things...

The load balancer device will contain these things... 

But, Im not attached to either, just thought I should chime in even though it may not make a difference.'}, {'account_id': 10980, 'date': '2014-09-04 20:59:23.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 10273, 'date': '2014-09-04 21:14:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

Also, not sure if we need oactavia/tests/unit/openstack/common* since that code is from outside our repo and we won't be changing it locally.

Otherwise, I think that looks good."}, {'account_id': 10980, 'date': '2014-09-04 21:27:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Port flavor-extra-data extension to v2.1 framework

This patch port v2 flavor-extra-data extension and adapts it to the
v2.1 API framework. API behaviour is identical.

- unittest code modified to share testing with both v2/v2.1

NOTE - adding extra attribute "ephemeral" in sample files to pass the tests
as "flavor_manage" plugin is not converted to V2.1.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I83403a17eed3a0f6c9242f7d553e444e45f37103

commit_message:
replaced incorrect reference to nova-manage with keystone-manage

This is a reference to nova-manage in a keystone specific
section. The correct tool is keystone-manage.

Change-Id: I5ec435228a65e0731482a622bbc18a5215a24f20
Closes-Bug: 1366144

commit_message:
Error on _ldap_get_list without attrlist value

The _ldap_get_list() on LDAP common library is not validating
attrlist when it has not value. This attribute should have some
value before be send it to LDAP search. If not, it causes an
unexpected UnicodeDecodeError.

Change-Id: I913ec9e1f8cf7283a98022a8445c45f4394251e6
Closes-Bug: #1358330

commit_message:
Make sure server works in network_advanced_server_ops

Before starting the test which may shutdown the server make sure it came up all the way. If we
turn the server off to quickly we trigger a bug in cirros where it
thinks it wrote out the ssh-key but didn't. Also its a good idea to make
sure the server works before turning it off, since we expect it to work
when we turn it back on.

Change-Id: Ieb3db6af941519849579222919f6207b2da760d4
Closes-Bug: #1349617

commit_message:
Error trapping for ldap2py

Closes-Bug: #1364521

I've recently come across a condition where the ldap driver will
return values from Active Directory which cannot be utf8 encoded.

Network captures show a clean attribute and value list, whereas if
I put in a debug statement to write out the values as
returned by the driver I can see a value like this:
?"?gZK??[J????

I propose that we drop values which cannot be encoded.

Change-Id: I98868721e2120abf9acbfd5578df8588376da0bc

commit_message:
Error class can accept message with format characters

Since the Error class is designed to simply accept any message string,
treating the message text as a format string causes errors if the
error message has format characters. This changes Error to have its
own format string that just echos the passed in message.

Change-Id: I1161d5e177dff860e180f845405d536e18222b23
Closes-Bug: 1361471

This commit adds client support for Metadata Definitions Catalog API
that is mentioned in Glance blueprint metadata-schema-catalog. This
patch covers all the calls exposed by the new API adding CRUD calls
for 4 new resources:
 * namespaces
 * properties
 * objects
 * resource types

Also unit tests for new functionality are added covering almost 100%
of the patch code.

DocImpact

commit_message:
Support for Metadata Definitions Catalog API

API calls and shell commands added in this patch:
- CRUD for metadefs namespaces;
- CRUD for metadefs objects;
- CRUD for metadefs properites;
- CRD for metadefs resource types and resource type associations.

Change-Id: I6d15f749038e8fd24fc651f0b314df5be7c673ef
Implements: blueprint metadata-schema-catalog-support
Co-Authored-By: Facundo Maldonado <facundo.n.maldonado@intel.com>
Co-Authored-By: Michal Dulko <michal.dulko@intel.com>
Co-Authored-By: Lakshmi N Sampath <lakshmi.sampath@hp.com>
Co-Authored-By: Pawel Koniszewski <pawel.koniszewski@intel.com>

commit_message:
Catch new urllib3 exception: ProtocolError

The new version of requests (2.4.0) has updated underlying urllib3
to version 1.9. Unfortunately urllib3 introduced new exception
ProtocolError. Because of that unit tests in glance are failing:
ProtocolError: ('Connection aborted.', gaierror(-2, 'Name or service not known'))

To solve this problem new urllib3 exception is caught in the same place
that the old one was. Unfortunately both exception are still in use so
I couldn't remove the old one.

Change-Id: I55eef98e734c59b9b627f182768a633b2b701e43
Closes-Bug: #1364893

this patch-set changes the behavior by deriving the configuration-parameters by datastore-version-id alone. this change in behavior is not mentioned in the blueprint, nor in the commit msg.

although this correction likely makes sense, this is concerning."}, {'account_id': 4240, 'date': '2014-03-13 07:26:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Datastore Configuration Parameters stored in db

Changes:
Add datastore configuration paramters to configuration model
Add ability to CRUD configuration parameters
adding a manage cmd to import the config params

partially implements blueprint configuration-parameters-in-db
Change-Id: I51d5281ba8922dc19c74e7c6e972f40e45416d50

commit_message:
Use safe_setup instead try block in setUpClass

To avoid resource leakage in case of exception in setUpClass,
some tests have try catch block in setUpClass and call tearDownClass
explicitly.
safe_setup decorator is for same purpose which should be
used instead.

commit_message:
Fix instance boot when Ceph is used for ephemeral storage

is_block_dev attribute was mistakenly set to True for RBD images
(we don't actually map RBD images to block devices in the *host*
system, but only in *guests*, so as far as the host system is
concerned an RBD image must not be treated like a system block
device). This led to a situation when mkfs was called for a non
existing file and failed when trying to create an ephemeral fs.

Closes-Bug: #1362221

Change-Id: I54c0d117a53bb61f278b2e137bd29a595548f5a1

[{'created': '2014-08-13 02:21:20.000000000', 'message': "Make floatingip-ip-delete atomic with neutron

The infra guys were noticing an issue where they were leaking floating ip
addresses. One of the reasons this would occur for them is they called
nova floating-ip-delete which first disassocates the floating-ip in neutron
and then deletes it. Because it makes two calls to neutron if the first one
succeeds and the second fails it results in the instance no longer being
associated with the floatingip. They have retry logic but they base it on
the instance and when they go to retry cleaning up the instance the floatingip
is no longer on the instance so they never delete it.

This patch fixes this issue by directly calling delete_floating_ip instead
of releasing first if using neutron as neutron allows this. I looked into
doing the same thing for nova-network but the code is written to prevent this.
This allows the operation to be atomic. I know this is sorta hackish that
we're doing this in the api layer but we do this in a few other places
too fwiw.

Change-Id: I53b0c9d949404288e8687b304361a74b53d69ef3
Closes-bug: 1356157

commit_message:
Make floatingip-ip-delete atomic with neutron

The infra guys were noticing an issue where they were leaking floating ip
addresses. One of the reasons this would occur for them is they called
nova floating-ip-delete which first disassocates the floating-ip in neutron
and then deletes it. Because nova-api makes two calls to neutron if the
first one succeeds and the second fails it results in the instance no longer
being associated with the floatingip. They have retry logic but they base it on
the instance and when they go to retry cleaning up the instance the floatingip
is no longer on the instance so they never delete it.

This patch fixes this issue by creating a new method
disassocate_and_delete_floating_ip which contains the different logic
needed to atomically do this for neutron rather than putting the logic
in the api layer to do something differently if one is using neutron.

This patch also adds additional code coverage for nova-network in the
delete floatingip case.

Closes-bug: 1356157
Change-Id: I53b0c9d949404288e8687b304361a74b53d69ef3

commit_message:
Fix TypeError in TestVolumeBootPattern

Commit eef192fc3c98a663f99f2fd944611bce0adffc0c changed
self._log_console_output() to self._log_console_output(self)
when dumping an instance's console output when ssh fails.

self in this case is the test class which is not an instance
(or list for that matter) so it blows up when we hit this
patch and masks the root failure.

Change-Id: Ieb68503a43269997a36c0a8b7f19f78ace97f251
Closes-Bug: #1363552

commit_message:
Fix race condition with vif plugging in finish migrate

The tempest test that does a resize on an instance from time to time fails
with neutron with a virtual interface timout error. The reason why this
occurs is that nova-compute calls a vifs_unplug() then vifs_plug() fairly
quickly and the neutron-agent doesn't realize this happens because the way
it detects this is via polling. This patch fixings this problem by passing
vifs_already_plugged=True to _create_domain_and_network to avoid waiting
for the neutron notifcation.

Initially, I thought this problem could be solved by setting
vifs_already_plugged=True if migrate.source_host == migrate_desk.dest_host
but it turns out that this race condition can still occur if migrated to
another host though it's fairly unlikely. Always setting
vifs_already_plugged=True ensures we never hit this issue on migrate.

Change-Id: I90424ad50ac993c4abb049aa0654a94b225b5ebb
Closes-bug: 1357599
Closes-bug: 1357476

Currently, even though $manage_haproxy_package is set to false there
is a call to a dependent resource Package['haproxy'], this commits
make sure that $manage_haproxy_package is honored.

OpenStack to a single account on the SolidFire cluster.
Previously, there was a mix of get and create accounts (check if
we already have one and create one if we need one).

This change introduces a combined get/create SolidFire account

'}]
commit_message:
Add a get and create account to SolidFire driver

Currently the SolidFire driver maps a single project-id from
OpenStack to a single account on the SolidFire cluster.
Previously, there was a mix of get and create accounts (check if
we already have one and create one if we need one).

This change introduces a combined get/create SolidFire account
method.  This will fix up things like accept_transfer to tenants
that may not have a SolidFire account yet (accounts were always
created on volume_create).

Change-Id: I4d7a4e8efcfc8f59d292c731256ea0d54b2651c6

commit_message:
Make NFS exports in generic driver permanent

Generic driver uses 'exportfs' utility for exports handling, but it stores
exports in temporary file /var/lib/nfs/etab and server loses all exports after
reboot. This change copies temp exports file to permanent exports file located
in /etc/exports after each action with exports and makes reexport of all
shares. After restart of server all exports will be restored from permanent
file.

Change-Id: I6a1e7074f18c70df5785d236c6f70c40731cda77
Closes-Bug: #1358688

PKI tokens were written in response to a request to deal with the chattiness of Keystone traffic in OpenStack.  There has been a concerted effort to migrate each of the pieces over to PKI tokens a step at a time, with the last piece that is still not there being Horizion.  Horizon is the only service that does not currently deploy with memcached, and so cannot store the large  PKI tokens.

Swift had a request to optimize traffic after the first request.  However, that is an additional optimization, and not sufficient reason to drop PKI tokens.

Without PKI tokens, we cannot go to epeheral tokesn, nor to Keystone to Keystone federation.  It enforces a single point of signing, and a single point of failure.  Instead of moving backwords, we need to address the real issues here.

PKI tokens are the default not only from Keystone, but also in the Puppet modules and the downstream deployments.  Most distributions have already worked through the PKI setup.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-29 23:37:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2014-07-30 02:32:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@ayoung, K2K federation has no bearing on if we internally use UUID or PKI tokens. K2K federation (as I understand it now) is going to use SAML which is not token specific. Will we still need signing certs, yes. do we need to use pki tokens, no.'}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2014-07-30 02:35:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@ayoung, based on the conversation today, the request form swift is *not* on after the first request, it is on *all* requests. The token is too big, period (and this is a complaint in *many* real deployments, every real deployment I've asked the question of has confirmed they use UUID). 

So a distribution does PKI setup, great, doesn't mean the deployer is using PKI tokens. 

This is a case where I think we need numbers from what is in use not the supported deployment options."}, {'account_id': 1916, 'date': '2014-07-30 06:31:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I would think PKI setup for token provider is no more or less complex than (say) SSL setup for the services, which is required for almost every real enterprise deployment. Same goes with Federation and K2K as they all involved asymmetric cryptography.

Now I do agree that token size is problematic. But is it fair to say that if we solved the service catalog problem, then PKI token would provide a measurable advantage over UUID token?'}, {'account_id': 9101, 'date': '2014-07-30 08:08:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I have a question: why does the PKI token id need to contain service catalog data? After search the code I find that only keystoneclient project will decrypt the PKI token id to get token data(but keystoneclient does not use the catalog data too...), other projects just take it as a string. So, how about remove catalog data when generate PKI token id?'}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2014-07-30 12:31:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

The move from UUID to PKI tokens flushed out a lot of the issues.  We would not have found them if we had not switched.

The UUID token approach has many drawbacks that we want to address:  only an admin user can validate, keystone persistence of tokens, and so forth.  The implementation, too, depends on memcached to be usable, so that the normal case for UUID  tokens avoids  revocation checking.

It does not matter to most people what we set in the defaults, as they are deploying with Puppet, and that has been changed to PKI tokens in the stackforge repo.  This is just indicating to the community that we do not plan to support PKI tokens.

The size issue with tokens is primarily, but not exclusively, due to the service catalog.  A CMS signed document has a minimun size of roughly 700 bytes;  there is a little bit we can do to tweak the data we put in there to drop about 150-200 bytes, and a PKIZ document with nothing in it is 900 bytes right now.

On the horizon side, the real problem is the service catalog:  Horizon needs the service catalog, and they really don;t need it in the token itself.  The catalog pushes the size of the session cookie over the 8K boundary on aregular basis.  The solution is either memcache, or drop the size of the service catalog.


PKIZ tokens do shift the network traffic forward, over the public internet, which might be the real complaint.

I'm fairly certain that there is a way to do authorization securely and distributed without token signing.  I'll revisit it, and we can come up with a plan."}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2014-07-30 17:33:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@ayoung, every request being 1k+ extra is absurd if you're considering how much each request to the services really is.

*Most* requests to any service (with exception of maybe glance or swift) is going to clock in a a few hundred bytes. You're asking the deployers and operators to eat 2x+ the network cost (from the end user, and the end user to eat 2x+ the network cost) for *auth data only*.

And we're not really arguing if we should or should not support PKI.

Even if we cut the token size down significantly (no service catalog) I firmly believe that the request will *still* be too big. 1k, 5k, 10k, that is a very large payload just to contain auth data.

Re: Horizon
So we are *requiring* memcache to get around a token issue that we created. Can we step back and look at how crazy this sounds? "Oh use this new shiny format, but because it's *HUGE* also deploy a whole caching infrastructure to your web front end that is only there to handle this *HUGE* data set we use for auth." If we have even a moderate load on a horizon install using PKI, that memcache cluster needs to have a bit of heft to it. You are also introducing another failure point (clustered / replicated / etc memcache is not really that good and has issues).

I think the way you do authorization without shifting the traffic to the public net is you go with something like how AWS works and use signed requests (ec2_token).'}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2014-07-30 17:34:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

signed requests = HMAC digest signed.'}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2014-07-30 17:41:24.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-30 17:41:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

But EC2 requests carry no authorization data (i.e. roles) right? So if you want RBAC, like what we are doing with policy, we still need to fill that gap somehow. Unless we are going to scrub policy in favor of a new system.'}, {'account_id': 6486, 'date': '2014-07-30 18:21:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2

So, in summary:

- UUID requires less setup than PKI (keystone-manage pki_setup, distributing those certs across multiple keystone nodes).

- UUID provides a better user experience for developers than PKI - the tokens are just shorter and thus more manageable. Copy/pasting them is easy. They take up less screen real estate, etc.

- UUID has fewer points of failure (it's just a callback to keystone; revocation is centralized) versus the challenges of certs (generation, expiration, distribution, file permissions, verification), additional dependencies (openssl), subprocess calls, etc.

- UUID and PKI effectively provide the same level of security.

- PKI's potential performance advantage is difficult to compare fairly against the performance of UUIDs. Performance gains in one area cause bottlenecks in others.

- Our users tend to switch to UUID, even with PKI as the default for the past 3 named releases.

- More bugs are filed against PKI's implementation than UUID's implementation (PKI's implementation is more complex, so that's arguably natural)."}, {'account_id': 1228, 'date': '2014-08-27 17:59:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 7175, 'date': '2014-08-27 19:28:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Admin-only validation isn't something I think we want in our tokens."}, {'account_id': 5623, 'date': '2014-08-27 23:04:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

Horizon should certainly be more flexible in it's token format handling, but I'm strongly in favor of not requiring a server side session store in horizon by default.  UUID tokens allow this.  Additionally, inherent HA of the current Horizon model of passing the token in signed cookies breaks when reliant on a server side store.  

We'll certainly work toward broader token format support, but I prefer UUID as the default."}, {'account_id': 4, 'date': '2014-08-27 23:08:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Set default token provider to UUID

This changes the default token provider to UUID, which affords a much
better deployer experience (no external dependencies and no additional
setup complexity) for deployers. It also provides a better end-user
experience (smaller, more manageable tokens) and appears to be the more
popular deployment option today, despite the current default to PKI.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: 1350000

Change-Id: I7fb2b191cce7a9762c33fee09e7e8d48a71a297b

commit_message:
Introduces eventlet executor for Glance Tasks

A sample import script to successfully import image from http or https
location is introduced. This should work on a devstack installtion.

Also, the following changes are introduced:-
1. An interface for implementing any other type of executor.
2. Provides namespace for keeping Tasks scripts.
3. A config for choosing deployer specific executor.
4. An interface for writing Tasks scripts.
5. A module for common script related methods.
6. Logic for limiting number of simultaneous tasks execution on the
Glance API server.

partially implements bp async-glance-workers
DocImpact

Change-Id: I382472fffd0fdad43573e72b2e78a9a6ed1e1f1a

commit_message:
Making a few MORE modules hacking 0.9.2 compliant

Global requirements has updating the version of hacking to a minimum of
0.9.2 and it has brought a whole slew of changes. This is tackling most
of the controllers, middleware, common code, and plugins (excluding
Symantec and kmip)

Change-Id: I8ee9713842be76d1f4be4abb2349105f1c020fdb

Add fixture for mock.patch.multiple

Add another fixture to support mock.patch.multiple() so that test suites
using that function don't have to import mock directly.

Change-Id: I58368dddda347410459d8f5a713e7395253c3697

commit_message:
Add new "volumes" context

For testing cinder snapshot operations, we needs to have users with
volumes before creating snapshots.

Change-Id: I356e14e5020d9a41bad1acbada76d658fa152c86
Implements: blueprint cinder-volume-context

Our current deploy ramdisks include functionality that is
duplicated from existing tools such as Dracut, and do not include
some features that those tools do.  Reimplementing our deploy
ramdisks to use Dracut would shrink our maintenance burden for
that code and allow us to take advantage of those additional
features.

commit_message:
Use Dracut for building ramdisks

Our current deploy ramdisks include functionality that is
duplicated from existing tools such as Dracut, and do not include
some features that those tools do.  Reimplementing our deploy
ramdisks to use Dracut would shrink our maintenance burden for
that code and allow us to take advantage of those additional
features.

Change-Id: Ibbbe1beb2d13b8ab43a9d9c32a1391a367039134

I don't think we want to do that, Gordon. Isn't it better to have more fine-grained than more coarse partitioning?

The way it currently is, the set of all firewalls (lb pools, vpns) will be partitioned across central agents. If we change it to endpoint discovery, we essentially make it so that only one agent polls *all* of those at a time.

My patch is actually just a hack for those pollsters that don't really have fine-grained resources, like floatingip, glance and kwapi, which only do one API call for all their samples.

If a pollster does multiple API calls, or the number of calls is even O(<#tenants/VMs/FWs...>), then I think we should definitely spread out those calls to different agents as much as possible. Compute pollsters already partition by VM, hardware by node, network services by fw/lb/vpn. I'll change Swift in a subsequent patch to partition by tenants as well.

Cheers,
Nejc"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-05 06:46:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

commit_message:
fix network discovery

patch stops network discovery from blindly polling if service is
not configured in keystone. this patch also refactors discovery so
it reuses generic endpoint discovery.

Change-Id: Ifb1482cdb1967cacfcd84d327467711a9d3e3151
Closes-Bug: #1361818

Each component is URL encoded.
Series name looks like name?tenant&region&dim1=val...

commit_message:
Ensure that mock.patch.stopall is called last

Fix the way we register mock.patch.stopall as a cleanup so that it is
called last to ensure that we do not then later try to stop any
individual mocks that will have already been stopped.

Change-Id: I50235eb1c8fae3e690fce63b27d18cafdefd8c4c
Partial-Bug: #1365678

commit_message:
Add crm shadow commit failure workaround

Try to commit the same shadow again if it fails.
Sometimes pacemaker fails to apply shadow
which does not differ from current configuration.
Manual reapplication succeeds and does not break
deployment.

Change-Id: Ie6f0fa8703fffeee27afc38a544f616e5cd97a29
Closes-bug: #1283062

commit_message:
Implements ProcessMonitor to watch over external processes

This class takes care of all the spawned external processes,
taking the administrator configured action in the case of any
of the external processes die unexpectedly.

Implements: blueprint agent-child-processes-status

Change-Id: I6bc7a415dde5723dac07589859796c2ffeef5b54

commit_message:
Improve batch write request

Implements batch operation support on storage driver layer
to enable opportunity to use native storage batch features

Implements: bp improve-batch-write-performance

Change-Id: If7fadeedc924a3d37bc2e0b683a9b323131a7a8b

commit_message:
Add field_labels parameter to cliutils.print_list

This patch allow setting custom heading for the resulting table.
This is required for cases, when the heading differs from field name
significantly, e.g. in Ironic client driver-list:
 hosts -> Active Host(s)

Change-Id: I02f41d2c0d5ab02856019b1cfc720a1136df9c2d
Closes-Bug: #1342391

[{'created': '2014-07-11 13:57:06.000000000', 'message': 'Set venv ownership to <service user name>:<service user name>

This patch was motivated by a recent issue we saw with Swift in
the overcloud.  The basic problem is a version mismatch between
the version of cffi installed in the Swift venv and the version
of cffi for which the python xattr module in the Swift venv
has pre-built support. The version of xattr installed has
pre-built support for cffi 0.8.2, whereas cffi 0.8.6 is installed.
Because of this, at swift-object start-up the cffi 0.8.6 module
attempts to build the appropriate C file in the python xattr
directory and fails because it doesn't have write permission
on the python xattr directory.  The reason is that the Swift venv
is installed by root, whereas Swift is run as the "swift" user.

To fix this we've modified os-svc-install to change the ownership
of the venv directories to swift:swift in the case of Swift, or
more generally <service user name>:<service user name> for any
given service.  This fix will prevent a recurrance of this ownership
problem exposed by the cffi version mismatch and related ownership
problems for Swift and for other services.

Change-Id: I2911645462c77ac39c2df1bc6cb914a97f87cbee

'}, {'created': '2014-07-15 11:41:32.000000000', 'message': 'Set venv ownership for services

This patch was motivated by a recent issue we saw with Swift in
the overcloud.  The basic problem is a version mismatch between
the version of cffi installed in the Swift venv and the version
of cffi for which the python xattr module in the Swift venv
has pre-built support. The version of xattr installed has
pre-built support for cffi 0.8.2, whereas cffi 0.8.6 is installed.
Because of this, at swift-object start-up the cffi 0.8.6 module
attempts to build the appropriate C file in the python xattr
directory and fails because it doesn't have write permission
on the python xattr directory.  The reason is that the Swift venv
is installed by root, whereas Swift is run as the "swift" user.

To fix this we've modified os-svc-install. There are two scenarios:

1.  If the common-venv element is in use, all venvs have group set
to OPENSTACK_VENV_GRP which is defined in the common-venv element
and defaults to "openstack".  This group is given rw permission on
all venvs, and each service user name is added to the group.

2.  Otherwise the ownership of the venv directories for each service
is set to <service user name>:<service user name>.  In the case of
Swift the ownership is set to swift:swift.

This fix will prevent a recurrance of the ownership problem exposed
by the cffi version mismatch and related ownership problems for
Swift and for other services.

Change-Id: I2911645462c77ac39c2df1bc6cb914a97f87cbee
Closes-Bug: #1340776

commit_message:
Set venv ownership for services

This patch was motivated by a recent issue we saw with Swift in
the overcloud.  The basic problem is a version mismatch between
the version of cffi installed in the Swift venv and the version
of cffi for which the python xattr module in the Swift venv
has pre-built support. The version of xattr installed has
pre-built support for cffi 0.8.2, whereas cffi 0.8.6 is installed.
Because of this, at swift-object start-up the cffi 0.8.6 module
attempts to build the appropriate C file in the python xattr
directory and fails because it doesn't have write permission
on the python xattr directory.  The reason is that the Swift venv
is installed by root, whereas Swift is run as the "swift" user.

To fix this we've modified os-svc-install. There are two scenarios:

1.  If the common-venv element is in use, all venvs have group set
to OPENSTACK_VENV_GRP which is defined in the common-venv element
and defaults to "openstack".  This group is given rw permission on
all venvs, and each service user name is added to the group.

2.  Otherwise the ownership of the venv directories for each service
is set to <service user name>:<service user name>.  In the case of
Swift the ownership is set to swift:swift.

This fix will prevent a recurrance of the ownership problem exposed
by the cffi version mismatch and related ownership problems for
Swift and for other services.

Change-Id: I2911645462c77ac39c2df1bc6cb914a97f87cbee
Closes-Bug: #1340776

commit_message:
HOT for Windows Active Directory Controller

The template deploys an Active Directory forest domain controller.

As there is the need of a Windows reboot after the install finishes,
exiting from the powershell script with the code 1001 signals to
cloudbase-init to trigger a reboot.

Change-Id: Ie171d55ffa69bb4c4f7381defd70a10d1c83213d
Co-Authored-By: Ionut Balutoiu <ibalutoiu@cloudbasesolutions.com>
Partially-Implements: blueprint windows-instances

commit_message:
Volume Replication implementation for IBM Storwize/SVC

Adds replication support to the IBM Storwize/SVC driver.
Supports IBM SVC stretched Cluster mode.

DocImpact

Change-Id: Id82623518c3508ad637f77d08699ffebcb44921e

commit_message:
Fix admin server doesn't report v2 support in Apache httpd

The Keystone server version response would only include v3 when
Keystone was running in Apache httpd. It should have also included
the v2.

Change-Id: Ib471539beda746d085adae1e72ab0dc1e0fb41e0
Closes-Bug: #1343579

commit_message:
Add test for single app loaded version response

There was no test that showed what the version response is when
only a single application (public or admin) is loaded.

The test shows that the response is incorrect for the admin
application.

Change-Id: I1fb1789c465d3f587077e3817a8eb2da54e28c63
Partial-Bug: #1343579

commit_message:
Change v3 admin_actions to v2.1

This patch changes v3 admin_actions API to v2.1 and make v2
unit tests share between v2 and v2.1, move v3 testcase to v2.1.
The differences between v2 and v3 are described on the wiki page
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/NovaAPIv2tov3 .

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api
Change-Id: I6fa4a8bd45d0f32f2a61bc6d8ff7e0fbb5fa7f26

commit_message:
Removing username/password requirement for swift objects

Previously, username and password were required by Data
Processing in order to create or access any objects (files)
stored in Swift.  With the use of managed trusts in the
service, the username and password will no longer be needed.
This change removes the username/password fields from
the data sources and job binaries panels.

Change-Id: Ifdfb961dd92fe61083238f79ec5884a60c93b368
Implements:  blueprint data-processing-swift-trust-auth

commit_message:
WIP explore issues with keystone discovery

port 35357 does not support a /v2.0 route, but everywhere in
devstack wants to use /v2.0 style work, therefore we need to
make requests at port 5000

committing to see what happens in the gate

Change-Id: I378edc3ad70315df17760e6176bedbedfaa5759f

commit_message:
Move _clients to cmd dir

Make clients public and accepting parameters. Python functions
should be not connected to environ, cause that is there only for
CLI use. This lib will be called e.g. from UI.

Making clients public unifies creating clients in all places,
it should help with future version changes of the clients.

Move _clients to CMD dir, where it is defaulted to os.environ
values and call public clients with those default values.

Change-Id: Ic490d9cfb4069809c8b3142f62f3dd40644a0cf7

commit_message:
Remove differences between Python 2.x and 3.x versions

We had these differences in requirements:
- mox in 2.x vs mox3 in 3.x: mox3 works for 2.x as well, so use it
  everywhere, mox3 version bumped to match global-requirements;
- mock in 2.x, absent in 3.x (in stdlib): it's installable on 3.x, so we
  can leave it in requirements;
- six in 2.x, absent in 3.x: is directly required by this lib, has been
  installed indirectly through hacking.

test-requirements files were identical.

This change allows us to build universal wheels and avoid confusion, see ML:
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-September/044663.html

Change-Id: I8bd2d561bf966c6dc1394a7d29d26f056d162fa9

commit_message:
Use https for all script sources

If a src is http and the html is served on https some browsers will deny
loading of the resource since it's not https.

Change-Id: I279bf5490e667e2db17926e65951723feb911e03

[{'created': '2014-09-01 14:55:29.000000000', 'message': 'Remove partial clean-up in Instance.destroy

Instance class implementation is based on OS::Nova::Server
resource in Heat and related networking resources. When deploy
called on Instance number of resources are allocated in Heat.

Some classes (e.g. descendants of Instance) can allocate other
resources that depends on presence of resources allocated by Instance,
for example HeatSWConfigInstance allocate OS::Heat::SoftwareDeployment
that depends on underlying OS::Nova::Server.

When Instance is destroyed and clean-up stage is finished underlying
resources are removed from stack. But since some resources still depend
on removed ones whole stack becomes invalid and deployment fails.

This change implements quick workaround by removing resource clean-up
in Instance class. Warning, this change introduce resource leak, cause
resoures are allocated during Instance deployment now will be deleted
only when whole Environment (and therefor stack) will be deleted.

Change-Id: I772f0b35918cd554fcbe1e830766ec23d5641176
Closes-Bug: #1359998

commit_message:
Remove partial clean-up in Instance.destroy

Instance class implementation is based on OS::Nova::Server
resource in Heat and related networking resources. When deploy
called on Instance number of resources are allocated in Heat.

Some classes (e.g. descendants of Instance) can allocate other
resources that depends on presence of resources allocated by Instance,
for example HeatSWConfigInstance allocate OS::Heat::SoftwareDeployment
that depends on underlying OS::Nova::Server.

When Instance is destroyed and clean-up stage is finished underlying
resources are removed from stack. But since some resources still depend
on removed ones whole stack becomes invalid and deployment fails.

This change implements quick workaround by removing resource clean-up
in Instance class. Warning, this change introduce resource leak, cause
resoures are allocated during Instance deployment now will be deleted
only when whole Environment (and therefor stack) will be deleted.

Change-Id: I772f0b35918cd554fcbe1e830766ec23d5641176
Closes-Bug: #1359998

commit_message:
Fix race condition when two Instances are deployed

Murano uses Heat to allocate OpenStack resources by creating and
updating one Heat stack. All changes to stack are stored in shared
variable exposed via call to environment.stack.updateStack.

Allocation of resources needed by Instance class is done in several calls
to environment.stack.updateStack therefor in case of simultaneous deployment
of two instances of class Instance race condition is possible.

Instance class was rewritten to have only one call to stack.updateStack
that is going to eliminate possible race condition.

P.S. This change also introduce new function mergeWith that can merge
two dicts.

Change-Id: Ib3b0be04e7d0b6107466bd5837278a12f01cf766
Closes-Bug: #1364824

commit_message:
Fix ARP cache poisoning vulnerability

ARP cache poisoning is not actually prevented by the firewall
driver 'iptables_firewall'. We are adding the use of the ebtables
command - with a corresponding ebtables-manager - in order to create
Ethernet frame filtering rules, which prevent the sending of ARP
cache poisoning frames.

Note:

    This commit is based entirely on Édouard Thuleau's patch, which
    he presented for review here:

        https://review.openstack.org/#/c/70067/

    His patch was abandoned. I have merely copied his code into the
    latest code base and made a few minor adjustments for this purpose.

    All credit for the patch should go to Édouard.

Closes-Bug: 1274034

Change-Id: Ie7242df4ea4181ca10a13a087740dacab1009a6c

commit_message:
Add Fujitsu ETERNUS DX support

 This driver had them correspond to FUJITSU ETERNUS DX.
 This driver supports ETERNUS DX S2 and the S3 series.

 The driver runs volume operations by communicating with the backend
 FUJITSU storage. It uses a CIM client in Python called PyWBEM to perform
 CIM operations over HTTP.

  Support protocols
  -Fibre Channel
  -iSCSI

  Support functions
  -create/delete volume
  -create/delete snapshot
  -attach/detach volume
  -list snapshots
  -create volume from snapshot
  -create volume from image
  -create volume from volume
  -create image from volume
  -extend volume
  -volume migration(host assisted)

driver-cert result
   fc : https://bugs.launchpad.net/cinder/+bug/1359467
   iscsi : https://bugs.launchpad.net/cinder/+bug/1359569

Change-Id: I7fe26dafae2f2db9130e020a34af73d0eb7ac719
Implements: blueprint fujitsu-dx-volume-driver

commit_message:
Unbreak debugging via testr

Unconditionally capturing stdout and stderr makes debugging quite
hard, since we can't see what we're typing.

Change-Id: I89b721b74821dac150dac9df74d31a8f9bbfe8da

[{'created': '2014-02-10 13:06:45.000000000', 'message': "OS::Savanna::Cluster resource implementation

* This patch implements resource for Hadoop cluster provisioned by
  Savanna based on Savanna's cluster template.
* Heat template for stack based on this resourse should have minimal set
  of fields needed to provision cluster. Example:
  http://paste.openstack.org/show/63874/
* To successfully provision cluster the following steps should be done:
  - Savanna enabled and works in your env
  - Savanna contains valid cluster template:
  http://docs.openstack.org/developer/savanna/userdoc/rest_api_v1.0.html#create-cluster-template
  - Savanna's image registry contains registered image with preinstalled
  Hadoop components:
  http://docs.openstack.org/developer/savanna/devref/quickstart.html#upload-image-to-glance

Related savanna's blueprint:
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/savanna/+spec/savanna-as-heat-resource

Implements blueprint savanna-as-heat-resource

commit_message:
Implement OS::Sahara::Cluster resource

* This patch implements resource for Hadoop cluster provisioned by
  Sahara based on Sahara's cluster template.
* Heat template for stack based on this resource should have minimal set
  of fields needed to provision cluster.
* To successfully provision cluster the following steps should be done:
  - Sahara enabled and working in your env
  - Sahara contains valid cluster template [1]
  - Sahara's image registry contains registered image with preinstalled
    Hadoop components [2]

[1] http://docs.openstack.org/developer/sahara/restapi/rest_api_v1.0.html#create-cluster-template
[2] http://docs.openstack.org/developer/sahara/devref/quickstart.html#upload-image-to-glance

Co-Authored-By: Pavlo Shchelokovskyy <pshchelokovskyy@mirantis.com>

Implements: blueprint sahara-as-heat-resource

Change-Id: If470511cbb88349f47a61a35b1a19ba7c68efd83

commit_message:
Moving code from __init__

Putting a function in the __init__ is considered a bad practice
in Python world. Moving it to CMD utils where it should belong.

Change-Id: I16279053202659c796bd6de2f4afdbf51b245a5a

I would be happy to see some description of typical WebSSO SAML2 workflow, as well as explanation who acts as a Service Provider (I think 'Keystone-webpage'?). All in all, there is 'SAML' and  'federated' in the blueprint title :-)"}, {'account_id': 10335, 'date': '2014-06-05 15:08:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(11 comments)

@Marek In the typical WebSSO SAML2 workflow when the user access a page protected by SAML in the web application (SP) he/she is redirect to a Discovery Service, if present. The user select the IdP and return to the web page with the entityID of the IdP. Then, the SP sends the user to the IdP specified in the entityID and the user can authenticate. After  the authentication succeed the user is sent back to the SP with a SAML assertion. The SP verify the SAML assertion and if it is correct will authenticate the user.

In the case of Keystone the problem is that the SP is Horizon but the authentication (IdP redirect, SAML verification, etc...) should be performed by Keystone.
This scenario is defined in SAML ECP profile but it is not supported now and it seems also in the near future.'}, {'account_id': 8978, 'date': '2014-06-05 16:07:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(29 comments)

Interesting. I agree that the current Horizon/Keystone authentication mechanism, where user's credentials are sent to Horizon is not inline with ID federation philosophy.

You mention an alternative solution where Horizon and Keystone use an external service to authenticate with. Since in the context of (SAML) federation, we are already relying on an
external authentication service (the IdP), this approach seems more beautiful to me. Why use a	second federation protocol inside OpenStack, since we are already using one with the IdP? But I
agree that there are still implementation issues that need to be solved, if we were to go in that direction.

Also, if using the OAuth 2 delegation mechanism, I'm not sure you need to register all the web applications that can authenticate against Keystone (as mentioned in the comments)."}, {'account_id': 5046, 'date': '2014-06-16 16:12:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

(9 comments)'}, {'account_id': 11717, 'date': '2014-06-16 20:08:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)'}, {'account_id': 8996, 'date': '2014-06-17 07:31:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

As Lance mentioned in one of his comments, a delegation mechanism is already implemented in Keystone: Trusts ( https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Keystone/Trusts ). This may be a sound alternative to implementing a new delegation mechanism with OAuth. What do you think ?'}, {'account_id': 10335, 'date': '2014-06-17 08:13:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

@Florent The problem with SAML federation is the user delegation to services where the user has not logged-in with SAML. The external service is requested so the user can log-in with SAML and then we have to implement a delegation mechanism towards keystone and horizon. I think this is a possible approach but I do not like it because requires to invent a new protocol and create a new service for the authentication where we already have keystone.

For the OAuth, the application registration is needed to avoid security problems. I added a link to OAuth 2.0 vulnerability it is possible to avoid if you have the applications endpoint registered.

I am reading the in-line comments and the delegation mechanism implemented and will answer soon.'}, {'account_id': 8978, 'date': '2014-06-17 09:22:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 9622, 'date': '2014-06-17 16:43:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

(12 comments)

*very* minor spelling nits.

small request to stick with "authorization" rather than "authorisation" 

Thanks, marco!'}, {'account_id': 8996, 'date': '2014-06-18 08:09:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

@Marco,	I agree that when using OpenStack through a web interface (like Horizon - unless the web interface is fully running client side), a delegation mechanism is the correct answer. Indeed, requests to Keystone and other OpenStack services are performed by the web server on behalf of the user, who delegates his rights to	the web	application.'}, {'account_id': 10335, 'date': '2014-06-19 09:28:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

++ to Adam's questions plus we need SecurityImpact in commit message."}, {'account_id': 6460, 'date': '2014-06-21 04:15:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

see inline comments'}, {'account_id': 8978, 'date': '2014-06-23 09:03:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

Two general comments and small inlined ones:

1) I am missing some description of the actors in your workflow example.

2) I think you should take into consideration how to bind authorization-code with unscoped token. Let's consider federated authentication. User is redirected to a Keystone-endpoint, goes to the IdP, goes back, his SAML assertion is parsed, groups dynamically mapped and normally Keystone returns unscoped token. As far as I understand it, you want Keystone to return authorization code, instead of the token. Now, given the fact there are some ongoing works to remove tokens from the backend (https://review.openstack.org/95976), in your solution Keystone will simply lose the token. You might need to somehow map them, either in cache (not a very good idea?) or in the backend. But then we are not fully 'token-in-db' free. Maybe Morgan Fainberg has some comments.

Also, mind that browsers don't persist headers between HTTP calls. If the server returns with HTTP 30x status code and e.g. stores token in the header, the next HTTP request, usually handled automatically by the browser, will not include token from the header.

This might be a crazy idea, but have you considered using some JavaScript clients? They could handle most of the logic, especially the redirections, headers and things like that. Plus we don't witness impersonation, since JS code is executed locally on your browser."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-06-23 09:03:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: -Verified

commit_message:
Fix network/secgroup scenario tests for ironic

Because the ironic nodes in devstack are all on a shared network
so they can communicate with the tftp server, all tenants must use
this same network in the scenario tests. This fixes up the networking
and security group tests to take this into account.

Code from the setUp() methods has been moved to a new, separately
called method, to speed up execution time when tests are skipped.
Since setUp() is executed even if a test is skipped, we can avoid
the time it takes to create an unneeded server by moving this to
a new method.

Co-Authored-By: Adam Gandelman <adamg@ubuntu.com>
Partial-Bug: #1361904

Change-Id: If711d69a79f19031dc1d8c529f1219680d22d9bb

commit_message:
Accept capitalized Sem-Ver headers

In Git, HTTP, and SMTP, header names generally have the first letter of
each word (including each part of a hyphenated word) capitalized.  In
all of the same cases, the actual headers are generally not considered
case-sensitive.  Accomodate this convention and the robustness principle
by performing lower-case comparisons of header names, and using
upper-case names in all of the documentation.

Change-Id: Iffa68107c8ff2aeaac92434da85155213e45a3cd

commit_message:
Fixes bug with index hash key

Fixes bug, that allowed to pass index hash
key that differs with primary hash key on
table creation.

Closes-bug: #1356584
Closes-bug: #1308971
Change-Id: I7b3cc2da926eb1b446de2ff212141beb38faccaf
