commit_message:
Fix ssh connection recreation in generic driver

When ssh connection died, generic driver tries remove broken connection by
passing nonexistent value, that is never assigned. Set expected value for
removal. Also added unittest for '_ssh_exec' method of generic driver due to
absense of it.

Change-Id: I7820a97d0aff52163b3ae56c9441323d7883f971
Closes-Bug: #1364848

commit_message:
Upgrades, add pre upgrade hook, copy release version files

For 5.0.x version we didn't have separate versions
for openstack releases, now we have openstack patching
and it's required for us to know what our system
is consists of. In order to do it, we need to copy
version.yaml files to `/etc/fuel/release_versions/`.

Change-Id: I37b5917eec519ed83531c77d30351811267bc9c2
Related-bug: #1365087

commit_message:
Upgrades, copy release versions during openstack upgrade

Openstack releases have different release
cycle and their own versions, files with
versions will be delivered in tar ball
and then user will be able to see the
list of versions which his system consists
of via nailgun api.

commit_message:
Refactor nested stack create/update/preview

The bug #1357433 was caused by the fact that stack parsing for a stack
resource on create/update/preview is pretty similar but repeated in all
three places.  This refactors them to move common logic to a single
place, making sure all validation in consistent and all params are
passed in the same way.

Closes-Bug: #1357433
Change-Id: I20ee7f9a6dbf047798b0cc954aa861f774e683b9

There are a few places in tests/conductor/test_manager.py where calls to
mock.assert_called_once() are made. The problem is that this isn't a valid
mock method, and 'assert_called_once' isn't a valid method of whatever is
being mocked. So it doesn't actually do anything.

This replaces the assert_called_once() calls with valid
assert_called_once_with() calls.

Change-Id: I7d46cf866bcce3b7e09bc556f2a1ddd10e4d1ca5
Partial-Bug: #1365745
"}]
commit_message:
mock.assert_called_once() is not valid method

There are a few places in tests/conductor/test_manager.py where calls to
mock.assert_called_once() are made. The problem is that this isn't a valid
mock method, and 'assert_called_once' isn't a valid method of whatever is
being mocked. So it doesn't actually do anything.

This replaces the assert_called_once() calls with valid
assert_called_once_with() calls.

Change-Id: I7d46cf866bcce3b7e09bc556f2a1ddd10e4d1ca5
Partial-Bug: #1365745

(2 comments)

Couple comments inline, but there are two main issues:

- I suggest you to wait when land stevebaker's patches with handling not_found exceptions.
I am sure that it will require correct rebase.

- Also while I look all files I thought about different solution. It seems obviously that we should
check resource_id always for all resources, so my idea is about moving this part in some shared part.
I mean that this check may be moved in resource class. I think it will allow to  handle this situation
better for all resources. 

if callable(getattr(self, 'handle_delete', None)):             
    handle_data = None
    if self.resource_id is not None:
        handle_data = self.handle_delete()
    yield                                                       


- and last case: I tend to recommend to cover all these changes by unittests."}, {'account_id': 9165, 'date': '2014-08-05 07:17:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Check resource_id is None before deleting

Check resource_id is None before deleting, if the
resource_id is None no need to call the client to
delete the resource, and also this check will avoid
some resources delete failure.

Change-Id: Ib024b98e4960bf3398d03e41fa89c73740070d4a

commit_message:
Use models.TimestampMixin from oslo.db

Since `ironic` and `oslo.db` uses `timeutils` from one place,
we can remove a temporary hack and re-use `TimestampMixin`
from common db code.

Change-Id: I48b2ce26484f1283ec65ae4f8dda57d962a8a875
Closes-Bug: #1354443

commit_message:
Add priority serializers for different modes

The commit introduce a new being - priority serializer. We need such
being since we should use different priority strategies for different
cases.

For example:

* We should deploy secondary controllers one-by-one in 5.0.x clusters.
* We should deploy all nodes one-by-one in case of patching.

Closes-Bug: #1364532
Change-Id: I77a445a51576b59aa188128047780af4db804312

commit_message:
Adds nova snapshot to the compute node

Snapshot 'nova-compute_installed' will contain the following
packages

    1. nova-compute-qemu
    2. python-guestfs
    3. libguestfs-tools

Installs and configures nova compute services.

This snapshot can be used to obtain stable running version of
controller node and can be used to revert back to this point in case
the students break the cluster.

Change-Id: Ide59062b30fdd9bd8c44f1b9c3e606ef1433f720

commit_message:
Volume Types tab with QOS Specs

This feature adds a new "Volume Types" tab to the Admin-Volumes panel, and
places QOS Specs on the panel. Future check-ins will add further
QOS Spec functionality, such as adding and deleting, etc.

Partially Implements: blueprint cinder-qos-specs
Closes-Bug: 1284506
Change-Id: I497f3bd00bb13356f5d0734f465cbf6feb02f781

commit_message:
Explicitly require simplejson

The simplejson library is a more up to date version
of the json module that is included in python 2.7+
and when used on python 2.6 the performance differences
are significant so to take advantage of these differences
we should try to use it when possible.

Change-Id: I8e46ec860608581ce55b8ebba53638433ffe7aa1

(2 comments)

It is my understanding that in case this code is merged migrated clusters will be unscalable. Assume you want to increase number of nodes. Sahara will generate a template where each Instance resource will be different from the initial template (created by old Icehouse Sahara). The whole cluster will be recreated. I see several ways to proceed:

 * somehow overcome that Heat limitation
 * leave a release note stating that scaling is not supported
 * leave a release note + make validation preventing old clusters to be scaled

BTW it just occurred to me that the same issue is related to all other changes we made to the template generation during this release'}, {'account_id': 8411, 'date': '2014-08-11 16:24:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Commit message was updated'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-11 16:24:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

(2 comments)

>It is my understanding that in case this code is merged migrated clusters will be unscalable.

Will heat recreate instance if scheduler hints change? In this case it can recreate the whole cluster even in case of usual scaling. Imagine we remove instance that is the first in aa chain. Scheduler hints will be changed for all other instances.'}, {'account_id': 7109, 'date': '2014-08-11 17:24:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

The old code worked because generally we always removed the last instances in the chain. I am not sure about cases with complex anti-affinity. Say if you have two node groups with datanodes and anti-affinity is enabled for datanodes. In that case seems like removing instances from the first node group will recreate all the instances in the second one.

On the other side anti-affinity defenitely worked fine in simple cases before (a single node group with anti-affinity enabled). After this code is merged, migrated clusters will become completely unscalable.

It just occurred to me that the same applies to environments where engine was switched from direct to heat. Seems like we need to implement good validation for that stuff + make a good doc.'}, {'account_id': 8411, 'date': '2014-08-11 17:31:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

>It just occurred to me that the same applies to environments where engine was switched from direct to heat.

Yeap, cluster becomes completely unusable after engine change. 

>Seems like we need to implement good validation for that stuff + make a good doc

I don't think that validation is possible. Also I don't think that this could be stopper for the feature. But I agree that we need release notes and doc about that."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-11 17:44:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-05 22:20:46.000000000', 'message': 'Fixed anti-affinity for HEAT engine

Added support of anti-afinity using heat provisioning engine even
when process spreaded across several noe groups.

Note, behavior of anti-affinity changed. Now Sahara will create one
server group for cluster and will assign all affected instances to it.
So, if anti-affinity enabled for datanode (`dn`) and tasktracker (`tt`)
Sahara will not assign node with `dn` and node with `tt` to the same
compute.

Also note, that server group support will be added to heat only in
juno-3. So, environment with up-to-date heat is required for the feature.

Closes-Bug: #1268610
Change-Id: I501438d84f3a486dad30081b05933f59ebab4858

commit_message:
Switched anti-affinity feature to server groups

Switched implementation of anti affinity to server groups for both
direct and heat engine.

Direct engine change is backward compatible. Sahara will detect if
old logic is used and will use the same logic for cluster scaling.

Note, behavior of anti-affinity changed. Now Sahara will create one
server group for cluster and will assign all affected instances to it.
So, if anti-affinity enabled for datanode (`dn`) and tasktracker (`tt`)
Sahara will not assign node with `dn` and node with `tt` to the same
compute.

Also note, that server group support will be added to heat only in
juno-3. So, environment with up-to-date heat is required.

Closes-Bug: #1268610
Implements: blueprint anti-affinity-via-server-groups
Change-Id: I501438d84f3a486dad30081b05933f59ebab4858

looking at "def _configure_logging(args)" my immediate thought was 'why only debug on info only' - but a) i guess adding explicit debug is the point here (and will probably be the most useful log level for issue investigation) and b) actually you'd have to change --debug to be a --log-level and expect a value and then you need to validate the passed values etc, so probably not desirable all things considered'}, {'account_id': 8449, 'date': '2014-09-03 09:03:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

("why only debug OR info only")'}, {'account_id': 8688, 'date': '2014-09-03 10:03:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

The patch as-is LGTM but it'd be more flexible if you provided a logging.conf file and a CLI option to specify the logging.conf to load which defaults to the file you provide.

Loading the file is easy with a logging.config.fileConfig call.

To switch to debug is then as easy as editing the file and swapping INFO to DEBUG. You could leave a comment saying this for the benefit of people who don't have loglevels etched into the brain like me.

This opens the door to more sophisticated logging later without any back-compatibility issues."}, {'account_id': 10992, 'date': '2014-09-03 17:53:00.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 9.'}, {'account_id': 10992, 'date': '2014-09-03 17:53:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 10992, 'date': '2014-09-03 18:00:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

@Marios @Alexis My initial intention was to add simple --debug command line parameter, to align os-cloud-config with other Openstack command line utilities. I absolutely agree that providing external config file option makes logging configuration much more flexible. Therefore, having --debug and --log-config in a mutually exclusive group looks like a good approach to me.

I replaced --log-file with --log-config to minimize number of command line arguments. Output file can be specified in external config, or even with bash redirection.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-03 19:03:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Verified+1

commit_message:
Enable standard logging in os-cloud-config

This review adds --debug and --log-config command line parameters to
utilities currently provided by os-cloud-config. By default (when
both parameters are omitted), logging is printed to stdout with
level INFO.

Change-Id: Ibd2c29e30fb23b080fb385b7c8b3236ccaa55e0e

1. There are some issues with this implementation highlighted in the comparison section on https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/cinder-pool-impl-comparison.

2. There is no clearly defined upgrade path.
  (i) How do you update the pools for already created volume?
  (ii) Where and how do you get the information about which pool a volume which was created before applying pools belong to when pools get implemented.
  (iii) Whats the procedure for upgrade? Is there any downtime or not? if yes then how long?

3. In the RFC you define pool host as host@backend@pool but in the code you deal with host@backend:pool. This is inconsistent.

4. How does backup and restore get affected by it?

5. How do you deal with the new feature consistency groups using this approach?'}, {'account_id': 2759, 'date': '2014-06-25 17:59:02.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 14.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-06-25 17:59:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14:

For the drivers that put pool names into volume type extra specs, we need a way to see all of the possible pools specified in volume types at get_volume_stats() time.   The 3PAR drivers can use extra specs to specify a specific pool the admin wants the volume to be created.   When this lands the 3PAR driver will add a new config option to provide a possible list of pools to support.   But there is nothing preventing an admin from creating a new volume type with a new pool that cinder.conf doesn't have.   In which case, the 3PAR driver won't be reporting stats on that pool specified in the volume type.   

Is it possible to add a new parameter to get_volume_stats() that provides a list of volume types that are assigned to the instance being called?   Then any driver that uses pools in extra specs can then make sure they report all stats on pools listed in cinder.conf as well as extra specs."}, {'account_id': 5538, 'date': '2014-08-05 14:01:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 19: Code-Review+1

(3 comments)

Code looks good. I tried to, but wasn't completely able to wrap my head around Walter's suggestion and how 3PAR driver works...so I don't have an opinion there as of now.."}, {'account_id': 9924, 'date': '2014-08-05 15:30:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 19:

So the host format coming from the scheduler is now:  'hostname@backend:pool'.

I suspect a colon isn't the best choice of delimiter here, as the pool string could contain colons.  Consider a pool which is an NFS share of the form 'address:/path', which itself contains a colon (and IPv6 addresses also contain colons).  So this could be hard to parse reliably.  In such cases we will have to prefix our pool strings with something like '(pool)' to make parsing simple and robust."}, {'account_id': 11047, 'date': '2014-08-21 17:02:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 24: Code-Review+1

I'll give you a +1 because the current separator works for me, but someone had a real case for not using ':'."}, {'account_id': 2759, 'date': '2014-08-27 17:47:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 30:

Clinton, Mark,

Please review the latest patch set. One important new change in this set is the addition of 'get_pool()' API for driver.  Both of your drivers have been using pool before Cinder exposes pools to scheduler, so I assume all existing volumes created by your drivers must have been put to certain pool on the backends.  'get_pool()' is called during volume manager init_host() to fetch the pool name of existing volumes, thus volume manager will be able to update such pool info to DB."}, {'account_id': 11865, 'date': '2014-08-27 18:53:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 30:

Winston, is get_pool() mandatory for pool-aware drivers?  What breaks if it isn't implemented immediately?  Are there any other such changes pending?  Thanks!"}, {'account_id': 11865, 'date': '2014-08-27 23:44:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 30: Code-Review-1

Winston, the vol_utils.extract_host() method fails to extract the pool value when the pool is an NFS share (i.e. host = 'ubuntu14@nfs-cm:192.168.228.25:/cinder2'.  Please pick a better delimiter for the pool than ':' !"}, {'account_id': 11047, 'date': '2014-08-28 04:40:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 30: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)

manage_existing() doesn't work.  Couldn't find a host.  I hacked and found a couple places to fix to make it work.  See inline comments for 2 things that need fixing.  

Not sure about the 3rd thing -- get_pool() called for volume that does not exist.  Might have only been a side-effect because of the above, but probably at least needs some exception handling or clarification on what drivers should do if volume does not exist.  Throw exception or return None or return default CPG???"}, {'account_id': 2759, 'date': '2014-08-28 06:40:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 30:

(3 comments)

Walter, I will add explanation to the FIXME in host_manager.py.

Clinton, yes, get_pool() is mandatory for all drivers, but since NetApp has been using pools before this.  It's more important that your driver is able to provide correct pool info for the volume so that we can append 'pool' to volume[host] for those legacy volumes to avoid corner cases I mentioned in the commit message.  But it won't break for most cases though.  And I will change the delimiter to '#', what do you think?

Mark, for manage volume job, basically I think we should assume that admin has already specified which pool the volume is in, same assumption applies to volume migration as well.  We can relax the exact match a bit (to compare volume['host'] with host_state.host without pool), but there are corner cases which Cinder itself can't prevent or handle well if pool is not there for target volume.  And good catch for the key issue for get_all_host_states(), will fix it in next patch.

And thank you all for the review."}, {'account_id': 2759, 'date': '2014-08-28 10:31:34.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 31.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-28 15:14:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 31: Verified+1

[{'created': '2014-06-09 08:31:38.000000000', 'message': "RFC: Pool-aware Scheduler Support

Status: Work-In-Progress (rev 0.1)

This change introduces pool-aware scheduler to address the need for
supporting multiple pools from one storage controller.

Terminology
----------------------------------------
Pool - A logical concept to describe a set of storage resource that
can be used to serve core Cinder requests, e.g. volumes/snapshots.
This notion is almost identical to Cinder Volume Backend, for it
has simliar attributes (capacity, capability).  The main difference
is Pool couldn't exist on its own, it must reside in a Volume
Backend.  One Volume Backend can have mulitple Pools but Pools
don't have sub-Pools (meaning even they have, sub-Pools don't get
to exposed to Cinder, yet).  Pool has a uniqueue name in backend
namespace, which means Volume Backend can't have two pools using
same name.

Design
----------------------------------------
The workflow in this change is simple:
 1) Volume Backends reports how many pools and what those pools
 look like and are capable of to scheduler;
 2) When request comes in, scheduler picks a pool that fits the need
 most to serve the request, it passes the request to the backend
 where the target pool resides in;
 3) Volume driver gets the message and let the target pool to serve
 the request as scheduler instructed.

To support placing resources (volume/snapshot) onto a pool, these
pieces in Cinder currently are missing:
1. Volume Backends reporting capacity/capabilities at pool level;
2. Scheduler filtering/weighing based on pool capacity/capability
and placing volumes/snapshots to a pool of certain backend;
3. Record which pool a resource is located on a backend and passes
between scheduler and volume backend.

The missing piece 1 is solved by a) updating the format of
periodical volume stats message to adopt pool stats; b) altering
manager/driver to collect and report pool stats.  Below is an example
of the updated report message that contains 2 pools:

    capability = {
        'volume_backend_name': 'Local iSCSI', #\
        'vendor_name': 'OpenStack',           #  backend level
        'driver_version': '1.0',              #  mandatory/fixed
        'storage_protocol': 'iSCSI',          #- stats&capabilities

        'active_volumes': 10,                 #\
        'IOPS_provisioned': 30000,            #  optional custom
        'fancy_capability_1': 'eat',          #  stats & capabilities
        'fancy_capability_2': 'drink',        #/

        'pools': [
            {'pool_name': '1st pool',         #\
             'total_capacity_gb': 500,        #  mandatory stats for
             'free_capacity_gb': 230,         #  pools
             'allocated_capacity_gb': 270,    # |
             'QoS_support': 'False',          # |
             'reserved_percentage': 0,        #/

             'dying_disks': 100,              #\
             'super_hero_1': 'spider-man',    #  optional custom
             'super_hero_2': 'flash',         #  stats & capabilities
             'super_hero_3': 'neoncat'        #/
             },
            {'pool_name': '2nd pool',
             'total_capacity_gb': 1024,
             'free_capacity_gb': 1024,
             'allocated_capacity_gb': 0,
             'QoS_support': 'False',
             'reserved_percentage': 0,

             'dying_disks': 200,
             'super_hero_1': 'superman',
             'super_hero_2': ' ',
             'super_hero_2': 'Hulk',
             }
        ]
    }

Notice that there are now two levels of mandatory/fixed stats &
capabilities that every volume driver should report.

The scheduler change is mostly done in scheduler/host_manager.py:
* HostState adds a list element to hold PoolState(s) (a HostState sub-
class).  Each PoolState can be treated like a HostState since it has
as much information as HostState and also share the same structure.
HostState.update_capabilities()/update_from_volume_capability() are
changed to handle both legacy and new report messages.
* HostManager.get_all_host_states() now returns a PoolState iterator
that includes all pools scheduler tracks.  To filters and weighers,
PoolState() and HostState() are identical, thus there is no need to
change filters and weighers since they are dealing with same kind of
information and exact same data strucuture as before.  What filter
and weigher deals with looks like this:
    # Before this chagne
      HostState() for Backend 1
         ...
      HostState() for Backend N
    # After this change
      PoolState() for Backend 1 Pool 1
         ...
      PoolState() for Backend 1 Pool N

        ...

      PoolState() for Backend N Pool 1
         ...
      PoolState() for Backend N Pool N

With this change, filter scheduler will pick a pool@host instead of a
host.

Now that we are able to report and decide at pool level, the 3rd
missing piece is easy to fix.  Just like how multi-backend
volume service is supported, we encoded pool name into 'host' field
of Volume table.  The 'host' field is now 'host@backend@pool'. Notice
that this change doesn't mean that cinder-volume service will have to
subscribe to multiple RPC channels.  There is no need to mess with
message queue subscription at all because we did a little trick when
determining RPC target in VolumeRPCAPI: correct host info like
'host@backend' is extracted from 'host@backend@pool' before sending
RPC messages.  Therefore, once scheduler decides which pool on a
backend shall serve a request, it updates 'host' field of the volume
record in DB to be like 'host@backend@pool', but it still sends RPC
message to 'host@backend' which cinder-volume is listening to.

Other changes are done in this WIP patch:

* Add 'enabled_pools' configure option to volume driver, this option
is per driver (thus per backend). Look at following cinder.conf
snippet.
  ...
  enabled_backends=back1,back2
  [back1]
  enabled_pools=pool1,pool2
  [back2]
  enabled_pools=foo,bar
  ...
* Change get_volume_stats() in ISCSIVolumeDriver/ISERDriver to include
pool stats.

Limitation/Known Issue
----------------------------------------
Drivers want to support pools need to update, but they should work
just like they used to without any change.

How About Upgrade For Running System?
----------------------------------------
To be added.

Change-Id: Id8eacb8baeb56558aa3d9de19402e2075822b7b4

             'super_hero_1': 'spider-man',    #  optional custom
             'super_hero_2': 'flash',         #  stats & capabilities
             'super_hero_3': 'neoncat'        #/
             },
            {'pool_name': '2nd pool',
             'total_capacity_gb': 1024,
             'free_capacity_gb': 1024,
             'allocated_capacity_gb': 0,
             'QoS_support': 'False',
             'reserved_percentage': 0,

             'dying_disks': 200,
             'super_hero_1': 'superman',
             'super_hero_2': ' ',
             'super_hero_2': 'Hulk',
             }
        ]
    }

Notice that there are now two levels of mandatory/fixed stats &
capabilities that every volume driver should report.

The scheduler change is mostly done in scheduler/host_manager.py:
* HostState adds a list element to hold PoolState(s) (a HostState sub-
class).  Each PoolState can be treated like a HostState since it has
as much information as HostState and also share the same structure.
HostState.update_capabilities()/update_from_volume_capability() are
changed to handle both legacy and new report messages.

that includes all pools scheduler tracks.  To filters and weighers,

change filters and weighers since they are dealing with same kind of
information and exact same data strucuture as before.  What filter
and weigher deals with looks like this:

      HostState() for Backend N

        ...

      PoolState() for Backend N Pool 1
         ...
      PoolState() for Backend N Pool N

With this change, filter scheduler will pick a pool@host instead of a
host.

missing piece is easy to fix.  Just like how multi-backend
volume service is supported, we encoded pool name into 'host' field
of Volume table.  The 'host' field is now 'host@backend@pool'. Notice
that this change doesn't mean that cinder-volume service will have to
subscribe to multiple RPC channels.  There is no need to mess with
message queue subscription at all because we did a little trick when
determining RPC target in VolumeRPCAPI: correct host info like
'host@backend' is extracted from 'host@backend@pool' before sending
RPC messages.  Therefore, once scheduler decides which pool on a
backend shall serve a request, it updates 'host' field of the volume
record in DB to be like 'host@backend@pool', but it still sends RPC
message to 'host@backend' which cinder-volume is listening to.

* Add 'enabled_pools' configure option to volume driver, this option
is per driver (thus per backend). Look at following cinder.conf
snippet.

  [back1]
  enabled_pools=pool1,pool2
  [back2]
  enabled_pools=foo,bar
  ...
* Change get_volume_stats() in ISCSIVolumeDriver/ISERDriver to include
pool stats.

Limitation/Known Issue
----------------------------------------
Drivers want to support pools need to update, but they should work
just like they used to without any change.

How About Upgrade For Running System?
----------------------------------------
To be added.

"}, {'created': '2014-06-10 17:09:35.000000000', 'message': "RFC: Pool-aware Scheduler Support

Status: Work-In-Progress (rev 0.1.2)

This change introduces pool-aware scheduler to address the need for
supporting multiple pools from one storage controller.

Terminology
----------------------------------------
Pool - A logical concept to describe a set of storage resource that
can be used to serve core Cinder requests, e.g. volumes/snapshots.
This notion is almost identical to Cinder Volume Backend, for it
has simliar attributes (capacity, capability).  The main difference
is Pool couldn't exist on its own, it must reside in a Volume
Backend.  One Volume Backend can have mulitple Pools but Pools
don't have sub-Pools (meaning even they have, sub-Pools don't get
to exposed to Cinder, yet).  Pool has a uniqueue name in backend
namespace, which means Volume Backend can't have two pools using
same name.

Design
----------------------------------------
The workflow in this change is simple:
 1) Volume Backends reports how many pools and what those pools
 look like and are capable of to scheduler;
 2) When request comes in, scheduler picks a pool that fits the need
 most to serve the request, it passes the request to the backend
 where the target pool resides in;
 3) Volume driver gets the message and let the target pool to serve
 the request as scheduler instructed.

To support placing resources (volume/snapshot) onto a pool, these
pieces in Cinder currently are missing:
1. Volume Backends reporting capacity/capabilities at pool level;
2. Scheduler filtering/weighing based on pool capacity/capability
and placing volumes/snapshots to a pool of certain backend;
3. Record which pool a resource is located on a backend and passes
between scheduler and volume backend.

The missing piece 1 is solved by a) updating the format of
periodical volume stats message to adopt pool stats; b) altering
manager/driver to collect and report pool stats.  Below is an example
of the updated report message that contains 2 pools:

    capability = {
        'volume_backend_name': 'Local iSCSI', #\
        'vendor_name': 'OpenStack',           #  backend level
        'driver_version': '1.0',              #  mandatory/fixed
        'storage_protocol': 'iSCSI',          #- stats&capabilities

        'active_volumes': 10,                 #\
        'IOPS_provisioned': 30000,            #  optional custom
        'fancy_capability_1': 'eat',          #  stats & capabilities
        'fancy_capability_2': 'drink',        #/

        'pools': [
            {'pool_name': '1st pool',         #\
             'total_capacity_gb': 500,        #  mandatory stats for
             'free_capacity_gb': 230,         #  pools
             'allocated_capacity_gb': 270,    # |
             'QoS_support': 'False',          # |
             'reserved_percentage': 0,        #/

             'dying_disks': 100,              #\
             'super_hero_1': 'spider-man',    #  optional custom
             'super_hero_2': 'flash',         #  stats & capabilities
             'super_hero_3': 'neoncat'        #/
             },
            {'pool_name': '2nd pool',
             'total_capacity_gb': 1024,
             'free_capacity_gb': 1024,
             'allocated_capacity_gb': 0,
             'QoS_support': 'False',
             'reserved_percentage': 0,

             'dying_disks': 200,
             'super_hero_1': 'superman',
             'super_hero_2': ' ',
             'super_hero_2': 'Hulk',
             }
        ]
    }

Notice that there are now two levels of mandatory/fixed stats &
capabilities that every volume driver should report.

* HostState adds a list element to hold PoolState(s) (a HostState sub-
class).  Each PoolState can be treated like a HostState since it has
as much information as HostState and also share the same structure.
HostState.update_capabilities()/update_from_volume_capability() are
changed to handle both legacy and new report messages.
* HostManager.get_all_host_states() now returns a PoolState iterator
that includes all pools scheduler tracks.  To filters and weighers,
PoolState() and HostState() are identical, thus there is no need to
change filters and weighers since they are dealing with same kind of
information and exact same data strucuture as before.  What filter
and weigher deals with looks like this:
    # Before this chagne
      HostState() for Backend 1
         ...
      HostState() for Backend N
    # After this change
      PoolState() for Backend 1 Pool 1
         ...
      PoolState() for Backend 1 Pool N

        ...

      PoolState() for Backend N Pool 1
         ...
      PoolState() for Backend N Pool N

With this change, filter scheduler will pick a pool@host instead of a
host.

Now that we are able to report and decide at pool level, the 3rd
missing piece is easy to fix.  Just like how multi-backend
volume service is supported, we encoded pool name into 'host' field
of Volume table.  The 'host' field is now 'host@backend@pool'. Notice
that this change doesn't mean that cinder-volume service will have to
subscribe to multiple RPC channels.  There is no need to mess with
message queue subscription at all because we did a little trick when
determining RPC target in VolumeRPCAPI: correct host info like
'host@backend' is extracted from 'host@backend@pool' before sending
RPC messages.  Therefore, once scheduler decides which pool on a
backend shall serve a request, it updates 'host' field of the volume
record in DB to be like 'host@backend@pool', but it still sends RPC
message to 'host@backend' which cinder-volume is listening to.

Other changes are done in this WIP patch:

* Add 'enabled_pools' configure option to volume driver, this option
is per driver (thus per backend). Look at following cinder.conf
snippet.
  ...
  enabled_backends=back1,back2
  [back1]
  enabled_pools=pool1,pool2
  [back2]
  enabled_pools=foo,bar
  ...
* Change get_volume_stats() in ISCSIVolumeDriver/ISERDriver to include
pool stats.

Limitation/Known Issue
----------------------------------------
Drivers want to support pools need to update, but they should work
just like they used to without any change.

How About Upgrade For Running System?
----------------------------------------
To be added.

"}, {'created': '2014-06-17 02:25:02.000000000', 'message': "RFC: Pool-aware Scheduler Support

Status: Work-In-Progress (rev 0.1.3)

This change introduces pool-aware scheduler to address the need for
supporting multiple pools from one storage controller.

Terminology
----------------------------------------
Pool - A logical concept to describe a set of storage resource that
can be used to serve core Cinder requests, e.g. volumes/snapshots.
This notion is almost identical to Cinder Volume Backend, for it
has simliar attributes (capacity, capability).  The main difference
is Pool couldn't exist on its own, it must reside in a Volume
Backend.  One Volume Backend can have mulitple Pools but Pools
don't have sub-Pools (meaning even they have, sub-Pools don't get
to exposed to Cinder, yet).  Pool has a uniqueue name in backend
namespace, which means Volume Backend can't have two pools using
same name.

Design
----------------------------------------
The workflow in this change is simple:
 1) Volume Backends reports how many pools and what those pools
 look like and are capable of to scheduler;
 2) When request comes in, scheduler picks a pool that fits the need
 most to serve the request, it passes the request to the backend
 where the target pool resides in;
 3) Volume driver gets the message and let the target pool to serve
 the request as scheduler instructed.

To support placing resources (volume/snapshot) onto a pool, these
pieces in Cinder currently are missing:
1. Volume Backends reporting capacity/capabilities at pool level;
2. Scheduler filtering/weighing based on pool capacity/capability
and placing volumes/snapshots to a pool of certain backend;
3. Record which pool a resource is located on a backend and passes
between scheduler and volume backend.

The missing piece 1 is solved by a) updating the format of
periodical volume stats message to adopt pool stats; b) altering
manager/driver to collect and report pool stats.  Below is an example
of the updated report message that contains 2 pools:

    capability = {
        'volume_backend_name': 'Local iSCSI', #\
        'vendor_name': 'OpenStack',           #  backend level
        'driver_version': '1.0',              #  mandatory/fixed
        'storage_protocol': 'iSCSI',          #- stats&capabilities

        'active_volumes': 10,                 #\
        'IOPS_provisioned': 30000,            #  optional custom
        'fancy_capability_1': 'eat',          #  stats & capabilities
        'fancy_capability_2': 'drink',        #/

        'pools': [
            {'pool_name': '1st pool',         #\
             'total_capacity_gb': 500,        #  mandatory stats for
             'free_capacity_gb': 230,         #  pools
             'allocated_capacity_gb': 270,    # |
             'QoS_support': 'False',          # |
             'reserved_percentage': 0,        #/

             'dying_disks': 100,              #\
             'super_hero_1': 'spider-man',    #  optional custom
             'super_hero_2': 'flash',         #  stats & capabilities
             'super_hero_3': 'neoncat'        #/
             },
            {'pool_name': '2nd pool',
             'total_capacity_gb': 1024,
             'free_capacity_gb': 1024,
             'allocated_capacity_gb': 0,
             'QoS_support': 'False',
             'reserved_percentage': 0,

             'dying_disks': 200,
             'super_hero_1': 'superman',
             'super_hero_2': ' ',
             'super_hero_2': 'Hulk',
             }
        ]
    }

Notice that there are now two levels of mandatory/fixed stats &
capabilities that every volume driver should report.

The scheduler change is mostly done in scheduler/host_manager.py:
* HostState adds a list element to hold PoolState(s) (a HostState sub-
class).  Each PoolState can be treated like a HostState since it has
as much information as HostState and also share the same structure.
HostState.update_capabilities()/update_from_volume_capability() are
changed to handle both legacy and new report messages.
* HostManager.get_all_host_states() now returns a PoolState iterator
that includes all pools scheduler tracks.  To filters and weighers,
PoolState() and HostState() are identical, thus there is no need to
change filters and weighers since they are dealing with same kind of
information and exact same data strucuture as before.  What filter
and weigher deals with looks like this:
    # Before this chagne
      HostState() for Backend 1
         ...
      HostState() for Backend N
    # After this change
      PoolState() for Backend 1 Pool 1
         ...
      PoolState() for Backend 1 Pool N

        ...

      PoolState() for Backend N Pool 1
         ...
      PoolState() for Backend N Pool N

With this change, filter scheduler will pick a pool@host instead of a
host.

Now that we are able to report and decide at pool level, the 3rd
missing piece is easy to fix.  Just like how multi-backend
volume service is supported, we encoded pool name into 'host' field
of Volume table.  The 'host' field is now 'host@backend@pool'. Notice
that this change doesn't mean that cinder-volume service will have to
subscribe to multiple RPC channels.  There is no need to mess with
message queue subscription at all because we did a little trick when
determining RPC target in VolumeRPCAPI: correct host info like
'host@backend' is extracted from 'host@backend@pool' before sending
RPC messages.  Therefore, once scheduler decides which pool on a
backend shall serve a request, it updates 'host' field of the volume
record in DB to be like 'host@backend@pool', but it still sends RPC
message to 'host@backend' which cinder-volume is listening to.

Other changes are done in this WIP patch:

* Change get_volume_stats() in ISCSIVolumeDriver/ISERDriver to include
pool stats.

Limitation/Known Issue
----------------------------------------
Drivers want to support pools need to update, but they should work
just like they used to without any change.

How About Upgrade For Running System?
----------------------------------------
To be added.

Change-Id: Id8eacb8baeb56558aa3d9de19402e2075822b7b4

missing piece is easy to fix.  Just like how multi-backend
volume service is supported, we encoded pool name into 'host' field
of Volume table.  The 'host' field is now 'host@backend@pool'. Notice
that this change doesn't mean that cinder-volume service will have to
subscribe to multiple RPC channels.  There is no need to mess with
message queue subscription at all because we did a little trick when
determining RPC target in VolumeRPCAPI: correct host info like

RPC messages.  Therefore, once scheduler decides which pool on a
backend shall serve a request, it updates 'host' field of the volume
record in DB to be like 'host@backend@pool', but it still sends RPC
message to 'host@backend' which cinder-volume is listening to.

This change introduces pool-aware scheduler to address the need for
supporting multiple pools from one storage controller.

Terminology
----------------------------------------
Pool - A logical concept to describe a set of storage resource that
can be used to serve core Cinder requests, e.g. volumes/snapshots.
This notion is almost identical to Cinder Volume Backend, for it
has simliar attributes (capacity, capability).  The main difference
is Pool couldn't exist on its own, it must reside in a Volume
Backend.  One Volume Backend can have mulitple Pools but Pools
don't have sub-Pools (meaning even they have, sub-Pools don't get
to exposed to Cinder, yet).  Pool has a uniqueue name in backend
namespace, which means Volume Backend can't have two pools using
same name.

Design
----------------------------------------
The workflow in this change is simple:
 1) Volume Backends reports how many pools and what those pools
 look like and are capable of to scheduler;
 2) When request comes in, scheduler picks a pool that fits the need
 most to serve the request, it passes the request to the backend

 the request as scheduler instructed.

To support placing resources (volume/snapshot) onto a pool, these
pieces in Cinder currently are missing:
1. Volume Backends reporting capacity/capabilities at pool level;
2. Scheduler filtering/weighing based on pool capacity/capability
and placing volumes/snapshots to a pool of certain backend;
3. Record which pool a resource is located on a backend and passes
between scheduler and volume backend.

periodical volume stats message to adopt pool stats; b) altering
manager/driver to collect and report pool stats.  Below is an example
of the updated report message that contains 2 pools:

    capability = {
        'volume_backend_name': 'Local iSCSI', #\
        'vendor_name': 'OpenStack',           #  backend level
        'driver_version': '1.0',              #  mandatory/fixed
        'storage_protocol': 'iSCSI',          #- stats&capabilities

        'active_volumes': 10,                 #\
        'IOPS_provisioned': 30000,            #  optional custom
        'fancy_capability_1': 'eat',          #  stats & capabilities
        'fancy_capability_2': 'drink',        #/

        'pools': [
            {'pool_name': '1st pool',         #\
             'total_capacity_gb': 500,        #  mandatory stats for
             'free_capacity_gb': 230,         #  pools
             'allocated_capacity_gb': 270,    # |
             'QoS_support': 'False',          # |
             'reserved_percentage': 0,        #/

             'dying_disks': 100,              #\
             'super_hero_1': 'spider-man',    #  optional custom
             'super_hero_2': 'flash',         #  stats & capabilities
             'super_hero_3': 'neoncat'        #/
             },
            {'pool_name': '2nd pool',
             'total_capacity_gb': 1024,
             'free_capacity_gb': 1024,
             'allocated_capacity_gb': 0,
             'QoS_support': 'False',
             'reserved_percentage': 0,

             'dying_disks': 200,
             'super_hero_1': 'superman',
             'super_hero_2': ' ',
             'super_hero_2': 'Hulk',
             }
        ]
    }

Notice that there are now two levels of mandatory/fixed stats &
capabilities that every volume driver should report.

The scheduler change is mostly done in scheduler/host_manager.py:
* HostState adds a list element to hold PoolState(s) (a HostState sub-
class).  Each PoolState can be treated like a HostState since it has
as much information as HostState and also share the same structure.
HostState.update_capabilities()/update_from_volume_capability() are
changed to handle both legacy and new report messages.
* HostManager.get_all_host_states() now returns a PoolState iterator

PoolState() and HostState() are identical, thus there is no need to
change filters and weighers since they are dealing with same kind of
information and exact same data strucuture as before.  What filter
and weigher deals with looks like this:

      HostState() for Backend 1
         ...
      HostState() for Backend N
    # After this change
      PoolState() for Backend 1 Pool 1
         ...
      PoolState() for Backend 1 Pool N

        ...

      PoolState() for Backend N Pool 1
         ...
      PoolState() for Backend N Pool N

host.

Now that we are able to report and decide at pool level, the 3rd
missing piece is easy to fix.  Just like how multi-backend
volume service is supported, we encoded pool name into 'host' field
of Volume table.  The 'host' field is now 'host@backend@pool'. Notice

subscribe to multiple RPC channels.  There is no need to mess with
message queue subscription at all because we did a little trick when
determining RPC target in VolumeRPCAPI: correct host info like
'host@backend' is extracted from 'host@backend@pool' before sending
RPC messages.  Therefore, once scheduler decides which pool on a
backend shall serve a request, it updates 'host' field of the volume
record in DB to be like 'host@backend@pool', but it still sends RPC
message to 'host@backend' which cinder-volume is listening to.

Other changes are done in this WIP patch:

* Change get_volume_stats() in ISCSIVolumeDriver/ISERDriver to include
pool stats.

Limitation/Known Issue
----------------------------------------
Drivers want to support pools need to update, but they should work
just like they used to without any change.

This change introduces pool-aware scheduler to address the need for
supporting multiple pools from one storage controller.

Terminology
-----------
Pool - A logical concept to describe a set of storage resource that
can be used to serve core Cinder requests, e.g. volumes/snapshots.
This notion is almost identical to Cinder Volume Backend, for it
has simliar attributes (capacity, capability).  The main difference
is Pool couldn't exist on its own, it must reside in a Volume
Backend.  One Volume Backend can have mulitple Pools but Pools
don't have sub-Pools (meaning even they have, sub-Pools don't get
to exposed to Cinder, yet).  Pool has a uniqueue name in backend
namespace, which means Volume Backend can't have two pools using
same name.
Legacy Volume - Volumes that were created prior pools are introduced.
There are several corner cases where legacy volumes could cause
issues, especially for those drivers used to do pools internally
(e.g. 3Par, NetApp).  Please refer to 'Limitation/Known Issues' for
details.

Design
------
The workflow in this change is simple:
 1) Volume Backends reports how many pools and what those pools
 look like and are capable of to scheduler;
 2) When request comes in, scheduler picks a pool that fits the need
 most to serve the request, it passes the request to the backend
 where the target pool resides in;
 3) Volume driver gets the message and let the target pool to serve
 the request as scheduler instructed.

To support placing resources (volume/snapshot) onto a pool, these
pieces in Cinder currently are missing:
1. Volume Backends reporting capacity/capabilities at pool level;
2. Scheduler filtering/weighing based on pool capacity/capability
and placing volumes/snapshots to a pool of certain backend;
3. Record which pool a resource is located on a backend and passes
between scheduler and volume backend.

periodical volume stats message to adopt pool stats; b) altering
manager/driver to collect and report pool stats.  Below is an example
of the updated report message that contains 2 pools:

    capability = {

        'vendor_name': 'OpenStack',           #  backend level
        'driver_version': '1.0',              #  mandatory/fixed
        'storage_protocol': 'iSCSI',          #- stats&capabilities

        'active_volumes': 10,                 #\
        'IOPS_provisioned': 30000,            #  optional custom
        'fancy_capability_1': 'eat',          #  stats & capabilities
        'fancy_capability_2': 'drink',        #/

        'pools': [
            {'pool_name': '1st pool',         #\
             'total_capacity_gb': 500,        #  mandatory stats for
             'free_capacity_gb': 230,         #  pools
             'allocated_capacity_gb': 270,    # |
             'QoS_support': 'False',          # |
             'reserved_percentage': 0,        #/

             'dying_disks': 100,              #\
             'super_hero_1': 'spider-man',    #  optional custom
             'super_hero_2': 'flash',         #  stats & capabilities
             'super_hero_3': 'neoncat'        #/
             },
            {'pool_name': '2nd pool',
             'total_capacity_gb': 1024,
             'free_capacity_gb': 1024,
             'allocated_capacity_gb': 0,
             'QoS_support': 'False',
             'reserved_percentage': 0,

             'dying_disks': 200,
             'super_hero_1': 'superman',
             'super_hero_2': ' ',
             'super_hero_2': 'Hulk',
             }

capabilities that every volume driver should report.

* HostState adds a list element to hold PoolState(s) (a HostState sub-

as much information as HostState and also share the same structure.

PoolState() and HostState() are identical, thus there is no need to
change filters and weighers since they are dealing with same kind of
information and exact same data strucuture as before.  What filter
and weigher deals with looks like this:
    # Before this chagne
      HostState() for Backend 1
         ...
      HostState() for Backend N
    # After this change
      PoolState() for Backend 1 Pool 1
         ...
      PoolState() for Backend 1 Pool N

      PoolState() for Backend N Pool 1
         ...

host.

missing piece is easy to fix.  Just like how multi-backend

of Volume table.  The 'host' field is now 'host@backend:pool'. Notice

subscribe to multiple RPC channels.  There is no need to mess with
message queue subscription at all because we did a little trick when

handle cases where there is needs to extract 'host', 'backend' or

To support placing resources (volume/snapshot) onto a pool, these
pieces in Cinder currently are missing:
1. Volume Backends reporting capacity/capabilities at pool level;
2. Scheduler filtering/weighing based on pool capacity/capability
and placing volumes/snapshots to a pool of certain backend;
3. Record which pool a resource is located on a backend and passes
between scheduler and volume backend.

The missing piece 1 is solved by a) updating the format of
periodical volume stats message to adopt pool stats; b) altering
manager/driver to collect and report pool stats.  Below is an example
of the updated report message that contains 2 pools:

    capability = {
        'volume_backend_name': 'Local iSCSI', #\
        'vendor_name': 'OpenStack',           #  backend level
        'driver_version': '1.0',              #  mandatory/fixed
        'storage_protocol': 'iSCSI',          #- stats&capabilities

        'active_volumes': 10,                 #\
        'IOPS_provisioned': 30000,            #  optional custom
        'fancy_capability_1': 'eat',          #  stats & capabilities
        'fancy_capability_2': 'drink',        #/

        'pools': [
            {'pool_name': '1st pool',         #\
             'total_capacity_gb': 500,        #  mandatory stats for
             'free_capacity_gb': 230,         #  pools
             'allocated_capacity_gb': 270,    # |
             'QoS_support': 'False',          # |
             'reserved_percentage': 0,        #/

             'dying_disks': 100,              #\
             'super_hero_1': 'spider-man',    #  optional custom
             'super_hero_2': 'flash',         #  stats & capabilities
             'super_hero_3': 'neoncat'        #/
             },
            {'pool_name': '2nd pool',
             'total_capacity_gb': 1024,
             'free_capacity_gb': 1024,
             'allocated_capacity_gb': 0,
             'QoS_support': 'False',
             'reserved_percentage': 0,

             'dying_disks': 200,
             'super_hero_1': 'superman',
             'super_hero_2': ' ',
             'super_hero_2': 'Hulk',
             }
        ]
    }

Notice that there are now two levels of mandatory/fixed stats &
capabilities that every volume driver should report.

The scheduler change is mostly done in scheduler/host_manager.py:
* HostState adds a list element to hold PoolState(s) (a HostState sub-
class).  Each PoolState can be treated like a HostState since it has
as much information as HostState and also share the same structure.
HostState.update_capabilities()/update_from_volume_capability() are
changed to handle both legacy and new report messages.
* HostManager.get_all_host_states() now returns a PoolState iterator
that includes all pools scheduler tracks.  To filters and weighers,
PoolState() and HostState() are identical, thus there is no need to
change filters and weighers since they are dealing with same kind of
information and exact same data strucuture as before.  What filter
and weigher deals with looks like this:
    # Before this chagne
      HostState() for Backend 1
         ...
      HostState() for Backend N
    # After this change
      PoolState() for Backend 1 Pool 1
         ...
      PoolState() for Backend 1 Pool N

        ...

      PoolState() for Backend N Pool 1
         ...
      PoolState() for Backend N Pool N

With this change, filter scheduler will pick a pool@host instead of a
host.

Now that we are able to report and decide at pool level, the 3rd
missing piece is easy to fix.  Just like how multi-backend
volume service is supported, we encoded pool name into 'host' field
of Volume table.  The 'host' field is now 'host@backend:pool'. Notice
that this change doesn't mean that cinder-volume service will have to
subscribe to multiple RPC channels.  There is no need to mess with
message queue subscription at all because we did a little trick when
determining RPC target in VolumeRPCAPI: correct host info like
'host@backend' is extracted from 'host@backend:pool' before sending
RPC messages.  Therefore, once scheduler decides which pool on a
backend shall serve a request, it updates 'host' field of the volume
record in DB to be like 'host@backend:pool', but it still sends RPC
message to 'host@backend' which cinder-volume is listening to.

Simliar action is done when creating backups for volumes.  host@backend
is extracted from volume['host'] so that correct backup service can be
picked.

* Change get_volume_stats() in ISCSIVolumeDriver/ISERDriver to include
pool stats, and change default totoal/free_capacity_gb from 'infinite'
to 0.
* Add logic in volume manager init_host() to detect legacy volumes and
try to update host info for them if driver is able to provide pool info.
* Add get_pool() driver API to return the pool name of given volume,
this help volume manager to handle legacy volumes, especially for those
backends already support pooling internally (e.g. 3Par, NetApp).
* Implement get_pool() for LVM driver to return volume backend name as
pool name.
* Add extract_host() helper function in cinder/volume/utils.py to help
handle cases where there is needs to extract 'host', 'backend' or
'pool' information from volume['host'].
* Add append_host() helper function in cinder/volume/utils.py to help
concatenate host and pool string into one for volume['host'] field.

Limitation/Known Issues
-----------------------
* The term 'host' in Cinder used to refer to 'backend', and it was
consistent from the view of end users/admins to Cinder interals.
Now that pool is exposed to Cinder scheduler, scheduler starts treating
different pools on same backend as different hosts.  Therefore, we have
to expose pool to admin at least, because migrating volume now has to
include pool in 'host' parameter in order to work.  As for end users,
the whole 'host' of volume equals storage backend idea works well for
them, so they can decide the policy of migration when retyping volumes,
or choose to create new volume on same or different host as/from
existing volumes.  Now it's *not* easy to hide pool from end user and
make retype or affinity filter work like before.  This change has a
speical code path for legacy volumes, to allow (potential) migration
between pools even migration_policy is set to 'never'.  But not every
driver has magic to move volumes to one pool to another at minimum
cost.  The inconsistency behavior between drivers (same command may
take totally different time to finish), which could be very confusing.

* Drivers want to support pools need to update, but they should work
just like they used to without any change except:
 - creating volume using same/different host hints with legacy volumes
 may NOT work as expected, because 'hostA' is considered different
 from 'hostA:pool0' and 'hostA:pool1'.  But legacy volume on 'hostA'
 might actually resides in pool0, only the driver has this knowledge.
 - retyping legacy volume issue as mentioned above.

Ultimate solution for all these corner cases is to update Cinder DB
to add 'pool' info for legacy volumes.  The problem is only the driver
knows such info, that is why we add a new driver API get_pool() to
so that volume manager is able to learn pool info from driver and
update host field of legacy volumes in DB.

PoolState() and HostState() are identical, thus there is no need to
change filters and weighers since they are dealing with same kind of
information and exact same data strucuture as before.  What filter
and weigher deals with looks like this:

      HostState() for Backend 1
         ...
      HostState() for Backend N
    # After this change
      PoolState() for Backend 1 Pool 1
         ...
      PoolState() for Backend 1 Pool N

        ...

      PoolState() for Backend N Pool 1
         ...
      PoolState() for Backend N Pool N

host.

missing piece is easy to fix.  Just like how multi-backend
volume service is supported, we encoded pool name into 'host' field
of Volume table.  The 'host' field is now 'host@backend#pool'. Notice

subscribe to multiple RPC channels.  There is no need to mess with
message queue subscription at all because we did a little trick when
determining RPC target in VolumeRPCAPI: correct host info like
'host@backend' is extracted from 'host@backend#pool' before sending
RPC messages.  Therefore, once scheduler decides which pool on a
backend shall serve a request, it updates 'host' field of the volume
record in DB to be like 'host@backend#pool', but it still sends RPC
message to 'host@backend' which cinder-volume is listening to.

picked.

pool name.

handle cases where there is needs to extract 'host', 'backend' or
'pool' information from volume['host'].

-----------------------
* The term 'host' in Cinder used to refer to 'backend', and it was
consistent from the view of end users/admins to Cinder internals.
Now that pool is exposed to Cinder scheduler, scheduler starts treating
different pools on same backend as different hosts.  Therefore, we have
to expose pool to admin at least, because migrating volume now has to
include pool in 'host' parameter in order to work.  As for end users,
the whole 'host' of volume equals storage backend idea works well for
them, so they can decide the policy of migration when retyping volumes,
or choose to create new volume on same or different host as/from
existing volumes.  Now it's *not* easy to hide pool from end user and
make retype or affinity filter work like before.  This change has a
speical code path for legacy volumes, to allow (potential) migration
between pools even migration_policy is set to 'never'.  But not every
driver has magic to move volumes to one pool to another at minimum
cost.  The inconsistency behavior between drivers (same command may
take totally different time to finish), which could be very confusing.

just like they used to without any change except:
 - creating volume using same/different host hints with legacy volumes
 may NOT work as expected, because 'hostA' is considered different

to add 'pool' info for legacy volumes.  The problem is only the driver
knows such info, that is why we add a new driver API get_pool() to
so that volume manager is able to learn pool info from driver and
update host field of legacy volumes in DB.

-------------------
DocImpact
For managing and migrating volumes, now user needs to provide pool
information as part of host string. For example:
  cinder manage --source-name X --name newX host@backend#POOL

This change introduces pool-aware scheduler to address the need for
supporting multiple pools from one storage controller.

Terminology
-----------
Pool - A logical concept to describe a set of storage resource that
can be used to serve core Cinder requests, e.g. volumes/snapshots.
This notion is almost identical to Cinder Volume Backend, for it
has simliar attributes (capacity, capability).  The main difference
is Pool couldn't exist on its own, it must reside in a Volume
Backend.  One Volume Backend can have mulitple Pools but Pools
don't have sub-Pools (meaning even they have, sub-Pools don't get
to exposed to Cinder, yet).  Pool has a unique name in backend
namespace, which means Volume Backend can't have two pools using
same name.
Legacy Volume - Volumes that were created prior pools are introduced.
There are several corner cases where legacy volumes could cause
issues, especially for those drivers used to do pools internally
(e.g. 3Par, NetApp).  Please refer to 'Limitation/Known Issues' for
details.

Design
------
The workflow in this change is simple:
 1) Volume Backends reports how many pools and what those pools
 look like and are capable of to scheduler;
 2) When request comes in, scheduler picks a pool that fits the need
 most to serve the request, it passes the request to the backend
 where the target pool resides in;
 3) Volume driver gets the message and let the target pool to serve
 the request as scheduler instructed.

To support placing resources (volume/snapshot) onto a pool, these
pieces in Cinder currently are missing:
1. Volume Backends reporting capacity/capabilities at pool level;
2. Scheduler filtering/weighing based on pool capacity/capability
and placing volumes/snapshots to a pool of certain backend;
3. Record which pool a resource is located on a backend and passes
between scheduler and volume backend.

The missing piece 1 is solved by a) updating the format of
periodical volume stats message to adopt pool stats; b) altering
manager/driver to collect and report pool stats.  Below is an example
of the updated report message that contains 2 pools:

    capability = {
        'volume_backend_name': 'Local iSCSI', #\
        'vendor_name': 'OpenStack',           #  backend level
        'driver_version': '1.0',              #  mandatory/fixed
        'storage_protocol': 'iSCSI',          #- stats&capabilities

        'active_volumes': 10,                 #\
        'IOPS_provisioned': 30000,            #  optional custom
        'fancy_capability_1': 'eat',          #  stats & capabilities
        'fancy_capability_2': 'drink',        #/

        'pools': [
            {'pool_name': '1st pool',         #\
             'total_capacity_gb': 500,        #  mandatory stats for
             'free_capacity_gb': 230,         #  pools
             'allocated_capacity_gb': 270,    # |
             'QoS_support': 'False',          # |
             'reserved_percentage': 0,        #/

             'dying_disks': 100,              #\
             'super_hero_1': 'spider-man',    #  optional custom
             'super_hero_2': 'flash',         #  stats & capabilities
             'super_hero_3': 'neoncat'        #/
             },
            {'pool_name': '2nd pool',
             'total_capacity_gb': 1024,
             'free_capacity_gb': 1024,
             'allocated_capacity_gb': 0,
             'QoS_support': 'False',
             'reserved_percentage': 0,

             'dying_disks': 200,
             'super_hero_1': 'superman',
             'super_hero_2': ' ',
             'super_hero_2': 'Hulk',
             }
        ]
    }

Notice that there are now two levels of mandatory/fixed stats &
capabilities that every volume driver should report.

changed to handle both legacy and new report messages.

change filters and weighers since they are dealing with same kind of
information and exact same data strucuture as before.  What filter
and weigher deals with looks like this:
    # Before this change
      HostState() for Backend 1
         ...
      HostState() for Backend N
    # After this change
      PoolState() for Backend 1 Pool 1
         ...
      PoolState() for Backend 1 Pool N

        ...

      PoolState() for Backend N Pool 1
         ...
      PoolState() for Backend N Pool N

host.

missing piece is easy to fix.  Just like how multi-backend
volume service is supported, we encoded pool name into 'host' field
of Volume table.  The 'host' field is now 'host@backend#pool'. Notice

subscribe to multiple RPC channels.  There is no need to mess with
message queue subscription at all because we did a little trick when
determining RPC target in VolumeRPCAPI: correct host info like
'host@backend' is extracted from 'host@backend#pool' before sending
RPC messages.  Therefore, once scheduler decides which pool on a
backend shall serve a request, it updates 'host' field of the volume
record in DB to be like 'host@backend#pool', but it still sends RPC
message to 'host@backend' which cinder-volume is listening to.

this help volume manager to handle legacy volumes, especially for those
backends already support pooling internally (e.g. 3Par, NetApp).
* Implement get_pool() for LVM driver to return volume backend name as
pool name.
* Add extract_host() helper function in cinder/volume/utils.py to help
handle cases where there is needs to extract 'host', 'backend' or
'pool' information from volume['host'].
* Add append_host() helper function in cinder/volume/utils.py to help
concatenate host and pool string into one for volume['host'] field.

Limitation/Known Issues
-----------------------

consistent from the view of end users/admins to Cinder internals.
Now that pool is exposed to Cinder scheduler, scheduler starts treating
different pools on same backend as different hosts.  Therefore, we have

so that volume manager is able to learn pool info from driver and

-------------------
DocImpact

information as part of host string. For example:

this help volume manager to handle legacy volumes, especially for those
backends already support pooling internally (e.g. 3Par, NetApp).
* Implement get_pool() for LVM driver to return volume backend name as
pool name.
* Add extract_host() helper function in cinder/volume/utils.py to help
handle cases where there is needs to extract 'host', 'backend' or
'pool' information from volume['host'].
* Add append_host() helper function in cinder/volume/utils.py to help
concatenate host and pool string into one for volume['host'] field.

Limitation/Known Issues
-----------------------
* The term 'host' in Cinder used to refer to 'backend', and it was
consistent from the view of end users/admins to Cinder internals.
Now that pool is exposed to Cinder scheduler, scheduler starts treating
different pools on same backend as different hosts.  Therefore, we have
to expose pool to admin at least, because migrating volume now has to
include pool in 'host' parameter in order to work.  As for end users,
the whole 'host' of volume equals storage backend idea works well for
them, so they can decide the policy of migration when retyping volumes,
or choose to create new volume on same or different host as/from
existing volumes.  Now it's *not* easy to hide pool from end user and
make retype or affinity filter work like before.  This change has a
speical code path for legacy volumes, to allow (potential) migration
between pools even migration_policy is set to 'never'.  But not every
driver has magic to move volumes to one pool to another at minimum
cost.  The inconsistency behavior between drivers (same command may
take totally different time to finish), which could be very confusing.

* Drivers want to support pools need to update, but they should work
just like they used to without any change except:
 - creating volume using same/different host hints with legacy volumes
 may NOT work as expected, because 'hostA' is considered different
 from 'hostA#pool0' and 'hostA#pool1'.  But legacy volume on 'hostA'
 might actually resides in pool0, only the driver has this knowledge.
 - retyping legacy volume issue as mentioned above.

Ultimate solution for all these corner cases is to update Cinder DB
to add 'pool' info for legacy volumes.  The problem is only the driver
knows such info, that is why we add a new driver API get_pool() to
so that volume manager is able to learn pool info from driver and
update host field of legacy volumes in DB.

User-Visible Change
-------------------
DocImpact
For managing and migrating volumes, now user needs to provide pool
information as part of host string. For example:
  cinder manage --source-name X --name newX host@backend#POOL
  cinder migrate UUID host@backend#POOL

commit_message:
Pool-aware Scheduler Support

This change introduces pool-aware scheduler to address the need for
supporting multiple pools from one storage controller.

Terminology
-----------
Pool - A logical concept to describe a set of storage resource that
can be used to serve core Cinder requests, e.g. volumes/snapshots.
This notion is almost identical to Cinder Volume Backend, for it
has simliar attributes (capacity, capability).  The main difference
is Pool couldn't exist on its own, it must reside in a Volume
Backend.  One Volume Backend can have mulitple Pools but Pools
don't have sub-Pools (meaning even they have, sub-Pools don't get
to exposed to Cinder, yet).  Pool has a unique name in backend
namespace, which means Volume Backend can't have two pools using
same name.
Legacy Volume - Volumes that were created prior pools are introduced.
There are several corner cases where legacy volumes could cause
issues, especially for those drivers used to do pools internally
(e.g. 3Par, NetApp).  Please refer to 'Limitation/Known Issues' for
details.

Design
------
The workflow in this change is simple:
 1) Volume Backends reports how many pools and what those pools
 look like and are capable of to scheduler;
 2) When request comes in, scheduler picks a pool that fits the need
 most to serve the request, it passes the request to the backend
 where the target pool resides in;
 3) Volume driver gets the message and let the target pool to serve
 the request as scheduler instructed.

To support placing resources (volume/snapshot) onto a pool, these
pieces in Cinder currently are missing:
1. Volume Backends reporting capacity/capabilities at pool level;
2. Scheduler filtering/weighing based on pool capacity/capability
and placing volumes/snapshots to a pool of certain backend;
3. Record which pool a resource is located on a backend and passes
between scheduler and volume backend.

The missing piece 1 is solved by a) updating the format of
periodical volume stats message to adopt pool stats; b) altering
manager/driver to collect and report pool stats.  Below is an example
of the updated report message that contains 2 pools:

    capability = {
        'volume_backend_name': 'Local iSCSI', #\
        'vendor_name': 'OpenStack',           #  backend level
        'driver_version': '1.0',              #  mandatory/fixed
        'storage_protocol': 'iSCSI',          #- stats&capabilities

        'active_volumes': 10,                 #\
        'IOPS_provisioned': 30000,            #  optional custom
        'fancy_capability_1': 'eat',          #  stats & capabilities
        'fancy_capability_2': 'drink',        #/

        'pools': [
            {'pool_name': '1st pool',         #\
             'total_capacity_gb': 500,        #  mandatory stats for
             'free_capacity_gb': 230,         #  pools
             'allocated_capacity_gb': 270,    # |
             'QoS_support': 'False',          # |
             'reserved_percentage': 0,        #/

             'dying_disks': 100,              #\
             'super_hero_1': 'spider-man',    #  optional custom
             'super_hero_2': 'flash',         #  stats & capabilities
             'super_hero_3': 'neoncat'        #/
             },
            {'pool_name': '2nd pool',
             'total_capacity_gb': 1024,
             'free_capacity_gb': 1024,
             'allocated_capacity_gb': 0,
             'QoS_support': 'False',
             'reserved_percentage': 0,

             'dying_disks': 200,
             'super_hero_1': 'superman',
             'super_hero_2': ' ',
             'super_hero_2': 'Hulk',
             }
        ]
    }

Notice that there are now two levels of mandatory/fixed stats &
capabilities that every volume driver should report.

The scheduler change is mostly done in scheduler/host_manager.py:
* HostState adds a list element to hold PoolState(s) (a HostState sub-
class).  Each PoolState can be treated like a HostState since it has
as much information as HostState and also share the same structure.
HostState.update_capabilities()/update_from_volume_capability() are
changed to handle both legacy and new report messages.
* HostManager.get_all_host_states() now returns a PoolState iterator
that includes all pools scheduler tracks.  To filters and weighers,
PoolState() and HostState() are identical, thus there is no need to
change filters and weighers since they are dealing with same kind of
information and exact same data strucuture as before.  What filter
and weigher deals with looks like this:
    # Before this change
      HostState() for Backend 1
         ...
      HostState() for Backend N
    # After this change
      PoolState() for Backend 1 Pool 1
         ...
      PoolState() for Backend 1 Pool N

        ...

      PoolState() for Backend N Pool 1
         ...
      PoolState() for Backend N Pool N

With this change, filter scheduler will pick a pool@host instead of a
host.

Now that we are able to report and decide at pool level, the 3rd
missing piece is easy to fix.  Just like how multi-backend
volume service is supported, we encoded pool name into 'host' field
of Volume table.  The 'host' field is now 'host@backend#pool'. Notice
that this change doesn't mean that cinder-volume service will have to
subscribe to multiple RPC channels.  There is no need to mess with
message queue subscription at all because we did a little trick when
determining RPC target in VolumeRPCAPI: correct host info like
'host@backend' is extracted from 'host@backend#pool' before sending
RPC messages.  Therefore, once scheduler decides which pool on a
backend shall serve a request, it updates 'host' field of the volume
record in DB to be like 'host@backend#pool', but it still sends RPC
message to 'host@backend' which cinder-volume is listening to.

Simliar action is done when creating backups for volumes.  host@backend
is extracted from volume['host'] so that correct backup service can be
picked.

Other changes are done in this patch:

* Change get_volume_stats() in ISCSIVolumeDriver/ISERDriver to include
pool stats, and change default total/free_capacity_gb from 'infinite'
to 0.
* Add logic in volume manager init_host() to detect legacy volumes and
try to update host info for them if driver is able to provide pool info.
* Add get_pool() driver API to return the pool name of given volume,
this help volume manager to handle legacy volumes, especially for those
backends already support pooling internally (e.g. 3Par, NetApp).
* Implement get_pool() for LVM driver to return volume backend name as
pool name.
* Add extract_host() helper function in cinder/volume/utils.py to help
handle cases where there is needs to extract 'host', 'backend' or
'pool' information from volume['host'].
* Add append_host() helper function in cinder/volume/utils.py to help
concatenate host and pool string into one for volume['host'] field.

Limitation/Known Issues
-----------------------
* The term 'host' in Cinder used to refer to 'backend', and it was
consistent from the view of end users/admins to Cinder internals.
Now that pool is exposed to Cinder scheduler, scheduler starts treating
different pools on same backend as different hosts.  Therefore, we have
to expose pool to admin at least, because migrating volume now has to
include pool in 'host' parameter in order to work.  As for end users,
the whole 'host' of volume equals storage backend idea works well for
them, so they can decide the policy of migration when retyping volumes,
or choose to create new volume on same or different host as/from
existing volumes.  Now it's *not* easy to hide pool from end user and
make retype or affinity filter work like before.  This change has a
speical code path for legacy volumes, to allow (potential) migration
between pools even migration_policy is set to 'never'.  But not every
driver has magic to move volumes to one pool to another at minimum
cost.  The inconsistency behavior between drivers (same command may
take totally different time to finish), which could be very confusing.

* Drivers want to support pools need to update, but they should work
just like they used to without any change except:
 - creating volume using same/different host hints with legacy volumes
 may NOT work as expected, because 'hostA' is considered different
 from 'hostA#pool0' and 'hostA#pool1'.  But legacy volume on 'hostA'
 might actually resides in pool0, only the driver has this knowledge.
 - retyping legacy volume issue as mentioned above.

Ultimate solution for all these corner cases is to update Cinder DB
to add 'pool' info for legacy volumes.  The problem is only the driver
knows such info, that is why we add a new driver API get_pool() to
so that volume manager is able to learn pool info from driver and
update host field of legacy volumes in DB.

User-Visible Change
-------------------
DocImpact
For managing and migrating volumes, now user needs to provide pool
information as part of host string. For example:
  cinder manage --source-name X --name newX host@backend#POOL
  cinder migrate UUID host@backend#POOL

implement blueprint: pool-aware-cinder-scheduler

Change-Id: Id8eacb8baeb56558aa3d9de19402e2075822b7b4

commit_message:
Fix default want_result value for event_finish_with_failure

Fix instance action event object method to match with other object
methods. Invoking this method without specifying want_result argument
should return object built from db values.

Related to blueprint compute-manager-objects-juno

Change-Id: I5f8cd66e4de20e730bcb8aceb2b97c3173e3870b

commit_message:
Ensure using int type for revocation_cache_time

Once set revocation_cache_time option for auth_token middleware,
it needs to be convrt to int before consuming by datetime.timedelta
function. Otherwise will cause WSGI service with this auth_token
middleware to die.

Change-Id: I6f7698f1e01603b5ecfe8b28f2282f9a1a8737b0
Closes-Bug: #1354269
